# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cites
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cites/acronym-p01] An **acronym** is an abbreviation formed using the initial letters of a multi-word name or phrase.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] Acronyms are often spelled with the initial letter of each word in all caps with no punctuation.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] In English, the word is used in two ways.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] In the narrow sense, an acronym is a sequence of letters (representing the initial letters of words in a phrase) when pronounced together as a single word, like *NASA*, *NATO*, or *laser*.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] In the broad sense, the term includes this kind of sequence when pronounced letter by letter (such as *GDP* or *USA*).
[src:cites/acronym-p01] Sources that differentiate the two often call the former acronyms and the latter **initialisms** or **alphabetisms**.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] However, *acronym* is popularly used to refer to either concept, and both senses of the term are attributed as far back as the 1940s.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] Dictionary and style-guide editors dispute whether the term *acronym* can be legitimately applied to abbreviations which are not pronounced as words, and there is no general agreement on standard acronym spacing, casing, and punctuation.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] The phrase that the acronym stands for is called its *expansion*.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] The *meaning* of an acronym includes both its expansion and the meaning of its expansion.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] The word *acronym* is formed from the Greek roots *akro-*, meaning 'height, summit, or tip', and *-nym*, 'name'.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] This neoclassical compound appears to have originated in German, with attestations for the German form *Akronym* appearing as early as 1921.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] Citations in English date to a 1940 translation of a novel by the German writer Lion Feuchtwanger.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] English lexicography and style guides differ on whether *acronym* should apply only to abbreviations pronounced as ordinary words or also to letter-by-letter initialisms.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] Some authorities accept or record the broader sense; others restrict *acronym* to word-pronounced forms and prefer *initialism* (or simply *abbreviation*) for the rest.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] Among sources that acknowledge the broader sense, attitudes range from neutral recording to prescriptive criticism.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] Some mainstream English dictionaries from across the English-speaking world affirm a sense of *acronym* that does not require its pronunciation as a word.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] English language usage and style guides which have entries for *acronym* generally criticize the usage that refers to forms that are not pronounceable words.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] In contrast, some style guides do support it, whether explicitly or implicitly.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] The 1994 edition of *Merriam-Webster's Dictionary of English Usage* defends the usage on the basis of a claim that dictionaries do not make a distinction.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] The BuzzFeed style guide describes CBS and PBS as "acronyms ending in S".
[src:cites/acronym-p01] Most of the dictionary entries and style guide recommendations regarding the term *acronym* in the twentieth century did not explicitly acknowledge or support the expansive sense.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] The Merriam–Webster's Dictionary of English Usage from 1994 is one of the earliest publications to advocate for the expansive sense, and all the major dictionary editions that include a sense of *acronym* equating it with *initialism* were first published in the twenty-first century.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] The 1989 edition of the *Oxford English Dictionary* only included the exclusive sense for *acronym* and its earliest citation was from 1943.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] In early December 2010, Duke University researcher Stephen Goranson published a citation for *acronym* to the American Dialect Society e-mail discussion list which refers to *PGN* being pronounced "pee-gee-enn", antedating English language usage of the word to 1940.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] Linguist Ben Zimmer then mentioned this citation in his December 16, 2010 "On Language" column about acronyms in *The New York Times Magazine*.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] By 2011, the publication of the 3rd edition of the *Oxford English Dictionary* added the expansive sense to its entry for *acronym* and included the 1940 citation.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] As the *Oxford English Dictionary* structures the senses in order of chronological development, it now gives the "initialism" sense first.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] Acronymy, like retronymy, is a linguistic process that has existed throughout history but for which there was little to no naming, conscious attention, or systematic analysis until relatively recent times.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] Like retronymy, it became much more common in the twentieth century than it had formerly been.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] American Telephone and Telegraph Company → AT&T).
[src:cites/acronym-p01] Some well-known commercial examples dating from the 1890s through 1920s include "Nabisco" ("National Biscuit Company"), "Esso" (from "S.O.", from "Standard Oil"), and "Sunoco" ("Sun Oil Company").
[src:cites/acronym-p01] Another field for the adoption of acronyms was modern warfare, with its many highly technical terms.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] The widespread, frequent use of acronyms across the whole range of linguistic registers is relatively new in most languages, becoming increasingly evident since the mid-twentieth century.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] As literacy spread and technology produced a constant stream of new and complex terms, abbreviations became increasingly convenient.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] The *Oxford English Dictionary* (*OED*) records the first printed use of the word *initialism* as occurring in 1899, but it did not come into general use until 1965, well after *acronym* had become common.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] In English, acronyms *pronounced as words* may be a twentieth-century phenomenon.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] Linguist David Wilton in *Word Myths: Debunking Linguistic Urban Legends* claims that "forming words from acronyms is a distinctly twentieth- (and now twenty-first-) century phenomenon.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] There is only one known pre-twentieth-century [English] word with an acronymic origin and it was in vogue for only a short time in 1886.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] The use of Latin and Neo-Latin terms in vernaculars has been pan-European and pre-dates modern English.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] The earliest example of a word derived from an acronym listed by the *OED* is "abjud" (now "abjad"), formed from the original first four letters of the Arabic alphabet in the late eighteenth century.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] Some acrostics pre-date this, however, such as the Restoration witticism arranging the names of some members of Charles II's Committee for Foreign Affairs to produce the "CABAL" ministry.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] Acronyms are used most often to abbreviate names of organizations and long or frequently referenced terms.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] The armed forces and government agencies frequently employ acronyms; some well-known examples from the United States are among the "alphabet agencies" (jokingly referred to as "alphabet soup") created under the New Deal by Franklin D.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] Business and industry also coin acronyms prolifically.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] The rapid advance of science and technology also drives the usage, as new inventions and concepts with multiword names create a demand for shorter, more pronounceable names.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] One representative example, from the U.S.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] Navy, is "COMCRUDESPAC", which stands for "commander, cruisers destroyers Pacific"; it is also seen as "ComCruDesPac".
[src:cites/acronym-p01] Acronym use has been further popularized by text messaging on mobile phones with short message service (SMS), and instant messenger (IM).
[src:cites/acronym-p01] To fit messages into the 160-character SMS limit, and to save time, acronyms such as "GF" ("girlfriend"), "LOL" ("laughing out loud"), and "DL" ("download" or "down low") have become popular.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] Some prescriptivists disdain texting acronyms and abbreviations as decreasing clarity, or as failure to use "pure" or "proper" English.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] Others point out that languages have always continually changed, and argue that acronyms should be embraced as inevitable, or as innovation that adapts the language to changing circumstances.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] In this view, the modern practice is just the "proper" English of the current generation of speakers, much like the earlier abbreviation of corporation names on ticker tape or newspapers.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] Exact pronunciation of "word acronyms" (those pronounced as words rather than sounded out as individual letters) often vary by speaker population.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] These may be regional, occupational, or generational differences, or simply personal preference.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] For instance, there have been decades of online debate about how to pronounce GIF (/ɡɪf/ or /dʒɪf/) and BIOS (/ˈbaɪoʊs/, /ˈbaɪoʊz/, or /ˈbaɪɒs/).
[src:cites/acronym-p01] Pronunciation may even vary within a single speaker's vocabulary, depending on narrow contexts.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] As an example, the database programming language SQL is usually said as three letters, but in reference to Microsoft's implementation is traditionally pronounced like the word *sequel*.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] In writing for a broad audience, the words of an acronym are typically written out in full at its first occurrence within a given text.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] Expansion at first use (EAFU) benefits readers unfamiliar with the acronym.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] Another text aid is an abbreviation key which lists and expands all acronyms used, a reference for readers who skipped past the first use.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] (This is especially important for paper media, where no search utility is available to find the first use.) It also gives students a convenient review list to memorize the important acronyms introduced in a textbook chapter.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] Expansion at first use and abbreviation keys originated in the print era, but they are equally useful for electronic text.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] While acronyms provide convenience and succinctness for specialists, they often degenerate into confusing jargon.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] This may be intentional, to exclude readers without domain-specific knowledge.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] New acronyms may also confuse when they coincide with an already existing acronym having a different meaning.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] Medical literature has been struggling to control the proliferation of acronyms, including efforts by the American Academy of Dermatology.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] Acronyms are often taught as mnemonic devices: for example the colors of the rainbow are ROY G.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] BIV (red, orange, yellow, green, blue, indigo, violet).
[src:cites/acronym-p01] They are also used as mental checklists: in aviation GUMPS stands for gas-undercarriage-mixture-propeller-seat belts.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] Other mnemonic acronyms include HOMES (for the North American Great Lakes) in geography, PAVPANIC in English grammar, and PEMDAS/BODMAS in mathematics.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] It is not uncommon for acronyms to be cited in a kind of false etymology, called a folk etymology, for a word.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] Such etymologies persist in popular culture but have no factual basis in historical linguistics, and are examples of language-related urban legends.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] For example, "cop" is commonly cited as being derived, it is presumed, from "constable on patrol", and "posh" from "port outward, starboard home".
[src:cites/acronym-p01] With some of these specious expansions, the "belief" that the etymology is acronymic has clearly been tongue-in-cheek among many citers, as with "gentlemen only, ladies forbidden" for "golf", although many other (more credulous) people have uncritically taken it for fact.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] Taboo words in particular commonly have such false etymologies: "shit" from "ship/store high in transit" or "special high-intensity training" and "fuck" from "for unlawful carnal knowledge", or "fornication under consent/command of the king".
[src:cites/acronym-p01] In English, abbreviations have previously been marked by a wide variety of punctuation.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] Obsolete forms include using an overbar or colon to show the ellipsis of letters following the initial part.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] The forward slash is still common in many dialects for some fixed expressions—such as in *w/* for "with" or *A/C* for "air conditioning"—while only infrequently being used to abbreviate new terms.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] The apostrophe is common for grammatical contractions (e.g.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] *don't*, *y'all*, and *ain't*) and for contractions marking unusual pronunciations (e.g.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] *a'ight*, *cap'n*, and *fo'c'sle* for "all right", "captain", and "forecastle").
[src:cites/acronym-p01] By the early twentieth century, it was standard to use a full stop/period/point, especially in the cases of initialisms and acronyms.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] Previously, especially for Latin abbreviations, this was done with a full space between every full word (e.g.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] This even included punctuation after both Roman and Arabic numerals to indicate their use in place of the full names of each number (e.g.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] Both conventions have fallen out of common use in all dialects of English, except in places where an Arabic decimal includes a medial decimal point.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] Particularly in British and Commonwealth English, all such punctuation marking acronyms and other capitalized abbreviations is now uncommon and considered either unnecessary or incorrect.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] The presence of all-capital letters is now thought sufficient to indicate the nature of the *UK*, the *EU*, and the *UN*.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] Forms such as *the U.S.A.* for "the United States of America" are now considered to indicate American or North American English.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] Even within those dialects, such punctuation is becoming increasingly uncommon.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] Some style guides, such as that of the BBC, no longer require punctuation to show ellipsis; some even proscribe it.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] Nevertheless, some influential style guides, many of them American, still require periods in certain instances.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] For example, *The New York Times Manual of Style and Usage* recommends following each segment with a period when the letters are pronounced individually, as in "K.G.B.", but not when pronounced as a word, as in "NATO".
[src:cites/acronym-p01] The logic of this style is that the pronunciation is reflected graphically by the punctuation scheme.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] When a multiple-letter abbreviation is formed from a single word, periods are in general not used, although they may be common in informal usage.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] "TV", for example, may stand for a *single* word ("television", for instance), and is in general spelled without punctuation (except in the plural).
[src:cites/acronym-p01] Although "PS" stands for the single English word "postscript" or the Latin *postscriptum*, it is often spelled with periods ("P.S.") as if parsed as Latin *post scriptum* instead.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] The slash ('/', or *solidus*) is sometimes used to separate the letters in an acronym, as in "N/A" ("not applicable, not available") and "c/o" ("care of").
[src:cites/acronym-p01] Inconveniently long words used frequently in related contexts can be represented according to their letter count as a numeronym.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] For example, "i18n" abbreviates "internationalization", a computer-science term for adapting software for worldwide use; the "18" represents the 18 letters that come between the first and the last in "internationalization".
[src:cites/acronym-p01] Similarly, "localization" can be abbreviated "l10n"; "multilingualization" "m17n"; and "accessibility" "a11y".
[src:cites/acronym-p01] In addition to the use of a specific number replacing that many letters, the more general "x" can be used to replace an unspecified number of letters.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] Examples include "Crxn" for "crystallization" and the series familiar to physicians for history, diagnosis, and treatment ("hx", "dx", "tx").
[src:cites/acronym-p01] Terms relating to a command structure may also sometimes use this formatting, for example gold, silver, and bronze levels of command in UK policing being referred to as Gx, Sx, and Bx.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] There is a question about how to pluralize acronyms.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] Often a writer will add an 's' following an apostrophe, as in "PC's".
[src:cites/acronym-p01] Turabian's *A Manual for Writers of Research Papers, Theses, and Dissertations*, writing about style in academic writings, allows for an apostrophe to form plural acronyms "only when an abbreviation contains internal periods or both capital and lowercase letters".
[src:cites/acronym-p01] Turabian would therefore prefer "DVDs" and "URLs" but not "Ph.D.s".
[src:cites/acronym-p01] Possessive plurals that also include apostrophes for mere pluralization and periods appear especially complex: for example, "the C.D.'s' labels" (the labels of the compact discs).
[src:cites/acronym-p01] In some instances, however, an apostrophe may increase clarity: for example, if the final letter of an abbreviation is "S", as in "SOS's" (although abbreviations ending with S can also take "-es", e.g.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] "SOSes"), or when pluralizing an abbreviation that has periods.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] A particularly rich source of options arises when the plural of an acronym would normally be indicated in a word other than the final word if spelled out in full.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] A classic example is "Member of Parliament", which in plural is "Members of Parliament".
[src:cites/acronym-p01] It is possible then to abbreviate this as "M's P", which was fairly common in mid-twentieth-century Australian news writing (or similar), and used by former Australian Prime Minister Ben Chifley.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] This usage is less common than forms with "s" at the end, such as "MPs", and may appear dated or pedantic.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] In common usage, therefore, "weapons of mass destruction" becomes "WMDs", "prisoners of war" becomes "POWs", and "runs batted in" becomes "RBIs".
[src:cites/acronym-p01] Abbreviations that come from single, rather than multiple, words—such as "TV" ("television")—are usually pluralized without apostrophes ("two TVs"); most writers feel that the apostrophe should be reserved for the possessive ("the TV's antenna").
[src:cites/acronym-p01] In some languages, the convention of doubling the letters in the acronym is used to indicate plural words: for example, the Spanish *EE.UU.*, for *Estados Unidos* ('United States').
[src:cites/acronym-p01] This old convention is still sometimes followed for a limited number of English abbreviations, such as *SS.* for *Saints*, *pp.* for the plural of 'pages', or *mss.* for *manuscripts*.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] The most common capitalization scheme seen with acronyms is all-uppercase (all caps).
[src:cites/acronym-p01] Small caps are sometimes used to make the run of capital letters seem less jarring to the reader.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] For example, the style of some American publications, including the *Atlantic Monthly* and *USA Today*, is to use small caps for acronyms longer than three letters; thus "U.S." and "FDR" are set in normal caps, but "nato" is set in small caps.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] The acronyms "AD" and "BC" are often smallcapped as well, as in: "From 4004 bc to ad 525".
[src:cites/acronym-p01] Where an acronym has linguistically taken on an identity as regular word, the acronym may use normal case rules, e.g. it would appear generally in lower case, but with an initial capital when starting a sentence or when in a title.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] Once knowledge of the words underlying such an acronym has faded from common recall, the acronym may be termed an **anacronym**.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] Examples of anacronyms are the words "scuba", "radar", and "laser".
[src:cites/acronym-p01] The word "an*acro*nym" should not be confused with the word "an*achro*nym", which is a type of misnomer.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] Words derived from an acronym by affixing are typically expressed in mixed case, so the root acronym is clear.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] For example, "pre-WWII politics", "post-NATO world", "DNase".
[src:cites/acronym-p01] In some cases a derived acronym may also be expressed in mixed case.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] For example, "messenger RNA" and "transfer RNA" become "mRNA" and "tRNA".
[src:cites/acronym-p01] Some publications choose to capitalize only the first letter of acronyms, reserving all-caps styling for initialisms, writing the pronounced acronyms "Nato" and "Aids" in mixed case, but the initialisms "USA" and "FBI" in all caps.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] For example, this is the style used in *The Guardian*, and *BBC News* typically edits to this style (though its official style guide, dating from 2003, still recommends all-caps).
[src:cites/acronym-p01] The logic of this style is that the pronunciation is reflected graphically by the capitalization scheme.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] However, it conflicts with conventional English usage of first-letter upper-casing as a marker of proper names in many cases.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] For example, *AIDS* stands for *acquired immunodeficiency syndrome*, which is not a proper name, while *Aids* is in the style of one.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] Some style manuals also base the letters' case on their number.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] While abbreviations typically exclude the initials of short function words (such as "and", "or", "of", or "to"), this is not always the case.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] Sometimes function words are included to make a pronounceable acronym, such as CORE (Congress of Racial Equality).
[src:cites/acronym-p01] Sometimes the letters representing these words are written in lower case, such as in the cases of "TfL" ("Transport for London") and *LotR* (*The Lord of the Rings*); this usually occurs when the acronym represents a multi-word proper noun.
[src:cites/acronym-p01] Numbers (both cardinal and ordinal) in names are often represented by digits rather than initial letters, as in "4GL" ("fourth generation language") or "G77" ("Group of 77").
[src:cites/acronym-p01] Large numbers may use metric prefixes, as with "Y2K" for "Year 2000".
[src:cites/acronym-p01] Exceptions using initials for numbers include "TLA" ("three-letter acronym/abbreviation") and "GoF" ("Gang of Four").
[src:cites/acronym-p01] Authors of expository writing will sometimes capitalize or otherwise distinctively format the initials of the expansion for pedagogical emphasis (for example, writing: "the onset of Congestive Heart Failure (CHF)" or "the onset of **c**ongestive **h**eart **f**ailure (CHF)").
[src:cites/acronym-p01] Capitalization like this, however, conflicts with the convention of English orthography, which generally reserves capitals in the middle of sentences for proper nouns; when following the AMA Manual of Style, this would instead be rendered as "the onset of congestive heart failure (CHF)".
[src:cites/acronym-p02] Some apparent acronyms or other abbreviations do not stand for anything and cannot be expanded to some meaning.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] Such pseudo-acronyms may be pronunciation-based, such as "BBQ" (*bee-bee-cue*), for "barbecue", and "K9" (*kay-nine*) for "canine".
[src:cites/acronym-p02] Pseudo-acronyms also frequently develop as "orphan initialisms": an existing acronym is redefined as a non-acronymous name, severing its link to its previous meaning.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] For example, the letters of the "SAT", a US college entrance test originally dubbed "Scholastic Aptitude Test", no longer officially stand for anything.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] This is common with companies that want to retain brand recognition while moving away from an outdated image: American Telephone and Telegraph became AT&T and British Petroleum became BP.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] *Russia Today* has rebranded itself as *RT*.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] American Movie Classics has simply rebranded itself as AMC.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] Genzyme Transgenics Corporation became GTC Biotherapeutics, Inc.; The Learning Channel became TLC; MTV dropped the name Music Television out of its brand; and American District Telegraph became simply known as ADT.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] "Kentucky Fried Chicken" went partway, re-branding itself with its initialism "KFC" to de-emphasize the role of frying in the preparation of its signature dishes, though they have since returned to using both interchangeably.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] The East Coast Hockey League became the ECHL when it expanded to include cities in the western United States prior to the 2003–2004 season.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] Pseudo-acronyms may have advantages in international markets: for example, some national affiliates of International Business Machines are legally incorporated with "IBM" in their names (for example, IBM Canada) to avoid translating the full name into local languages.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] Likewise, UBS is the name of the merged Union Bank of Switzerland and Swiss Bank Corporation, and HSBC has replaced the long name Hongkong and Shanghai Banking Corporation.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] The India-based JSW Group of companies is another example of the original name (Jindal South West Group) being re-branded into a pseudo-acronym while expanding into other geographical areas in and outside of India.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] Rebranding can lead to redundant acronym syndrome, as when Trustee Savings Bank became TSB Bank, or when Railway Express Agency became REA Express.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] A few high-tech companies have taken the redundant acronym to the extreme: for example, ISM Information Systems Management Corp. and SHL Systemhouse Ltd.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] Examples in entertainment include the television shows *CSI: Crime Scene Investigation* and *Navy: NCIS* ("Navy" was dropped in the second season), where the redundancy was likely designed to educate new viewers as to what the initials stood for.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] In some cases, while the initials in an acronym may stay the same, for what those letters stand may change.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] A *backronym* (or *bacronym*) is a phrase that is constructed "after the fact" from a previously existing word.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] For example, the novelist and critic Anthony Burgess once proposed that the word "book" ought to stand for "box of organized knowledge".
[src:cites/acronym-p02] A classic real-world example of this is the name of the predecessor to the Apple Macintosh, the Apple Lisa, which was said to refer to "Local Integrated Software Architecture", but was actually named after Steve Jobs' daughter, born in 1978.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] Contrived acronyms are deliberately designed to be apt for the thing being named (by having a dual meaning or by borrowing the positive connotations of an existing word).
[src:cites/acronym-p02] Some examples of contrived acronyms are *USA PATRIOT*, *CAN SPAM*, *CAPTCHA*, *DOGE* and *ACT UP*.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] The clothing company French Connection began referring to itself as *fcuk*, standing for "French Connection United Kingdom".
[src:cites/acronym-p02] The company then created T-shirts and several advertising campaigns that exploit the acronym's similarity to the taboo word "fuck".
[src:cites/acronym-p02] Contrived acronyms find frequent use as names of fictional agencies, with a famous example being frequent James Bond antagonist organization SPECTRE (Special Executive for Counterintelligence, Terrorism, Revenge and Extortion).
[src:cites/acronym-p02] Department of Defense's Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency (DARPA) is known for developing contrived acronyms to name projects, including *RESURRECT*, *NIRVANA*, and *DUDE*.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] The short-form names of clinical trials and other scientific studies constitute a large class of acronyms that includes many contrived examples, as well as many with a partial rather than complete correspondence of letters to expansion components.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] Examples widely known in medicine include the ALLHAT trial (Antihypertensive and Lipid-Lowering Treatment to Prevent Heart Attack Trial) and the CHARM trial (Candesartan in Heart Failure: Assessment of Reduction in Mortality and Morbidity).
[src:cites/acronym-p02] However, the purpose of clinical trial acronyms, as with gene and protein symbols, is simply to have a syntactically usable and easily recalled short name to complement the long name that is often syntactically unusable and not memorized.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] It is useful for the short name to give a reminder of the long name, which supports the reasonable censure of "cutesy" examples that provide little to no hint of it.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] But beyond that reasonably close correspondence, the short name's chief utility is in functioning cognitively as a name, rather than being a cryptic and forgettable string, albeit faithful to the matching of letters.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] At least one study has evaluated the citation impact and other traits of acronym-named trials compared with others, finding both good aspects (mnemonic help, name recall) and potential flaws (connotatively driven bias).
[src:cites/acronym-p02] Some acronyms are chosen deliberately to avoid a name considered undesirable: For example, *Verliebt in Berlin* (*ViB*), a German telenovela, was first intended to be *Alles nur aus Liebe* ('All for Love'), but was changed to avoid the resultant acronym *ANAL*.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] Likewise, the Computer Literacy and Internet Technology qualification is known as *CLaIT*, rather than *CLIT*.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] In Canada, the Canadian Conservative Reform Alliance (Party) was quickly renamed to the "Canadian Reform Conservative Alliance" when its opponents pointed out that its initials spelled CCRAP (pronounced "see crap").
[src:cites/acronym-p02] Two Irish institutes of technology (Galway and Tralee) chose different acronyms from other institutes when they were upgraded from regional technical colleges.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] Tralee RTC became the Institute of Technology Tralee (ITT), as opposed to Tralee Institute of Technology (TIT).
[src:cites/acronym-p02] Galway RTC became Galway-Mayo Institute of Technology (GMIT), as opposed to Galway Institute of Technology (GIT).
[src:cites/acronym-p02] The charity sports organization Team in Training is known as "TNT" and not "TIT".
[src:cites/acronym-p02] Technological Institute of Textile & Sciences, however, is still known as "TITS".
[src:cites/acronym-p02] George Mason University was planning to name their law school the "Antonin Scalia School of Law" (ASSOL) in honor of the late Antonin Scalia, only to change it to the "Antonin Scalia Law School" later.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] A **macronym**, or **nested acronym**, is an acronym in which one or more letters stand for acronyms (or abbreviations) themselves.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] The word "macronym" is a portmanteau of "macro-" and "acronym".
[src:cites/acronym-p02] Some macronyms can be multiply nested: the second-order acronym points to another one further down a hierarchy.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] VITAL, for example, which expands to "VHDL Initiative Towards ASIC Libraries" is a total of 15 words when fully expanded.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] Fully expanded, "RARS" might thus become "Regional Advanced Television Infrared Observational Satellite Operational Vertical Sounder Retransmission Service", which would produce the much more unwieldy acronym "RATIOSOVSRS".
[src:cites/acronym-p02] The latter are fully reducible in an attempt to "spell everything out and avoid all abbreviations", but the former are irreducible in that respect; they can be annotated with parenthetical explanations, but they cannot be eliminated from speech or writing in any useful or practical way.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] The name is thus itself more symbol than acronym, and its expansion cannot replace it while preserving its function in natural syntax as a name within a clause clearly parsable by human readers or listeners.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] A special type of macronym, the recursive acronym, has letters whose expansion refers back to the macronym itself.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] One of the earliest examples appears in *The Hacker's Dictionary* as MUNG, which stands for "MUNG Until No Good".
[src:cites/acronym-p02] With English terminology, discussions of languages with syllabic or logographic writing systems (such as Chinese, Japanese, and Korean), "acronyms" describe the short forms that take selected characters from a multi-character word.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] For example, in Chinese, 'university' (大學/大学, lit.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] 'great learning') is usually abbreviated simply as 大 ('great') when used with the name of the institute.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] So 'Peking University' (北京大学) is commonly shortened to 北大 (lit.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] 'north-great') by also only taking the first character of *Peking*, the "northern capital" (北京; *Beijing*).
[src:cites/acronym-p02] In some cases, however, other characters than the first can be selected.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] For example, the local short form of 'Hong Kong University' (香港大學) uses *Kong* (港大) rather than *Hong*.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] Many aspects of academics in Korea follow similar acronym patterns as Chinese, owing to the two languages' commonalities, like using the word for 'big' or 'great' i.e.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] *dae* (대), to refer to universities (대학; *daehak*, literally 'great learning' although 'big school' is an acceptable alternate).
[src:cites/acronym-p02] They can be interpreted similarly to American university appellations, such as "UPenn" or "Texas Tech".
[src:cites/acronym-p02] Some acronyms are shortened forms of the school's name, like how Hongik University (홍익대학교, *Hongik Daehakgyo*) is shortened to *Hongdae* (홍대, 'Hong, the big [school]' or 'Hong-U') Other acronyms can refer to the university's main subject, e.g.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] Korea National University of Education (한국교원대학교, *Hanguk Gyowon Daehakgyo*) is shortened to *Gyowondae* (교원대, 'Big Ed.' or 'Ed.-U').
[src:cites/acronym-p02] Other schools use a Koreanized version of their English acronym.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] The Korea Advanced Institute of Science and Technology (한국과학기술원, *Hanguk Gwahak Gisulwon*) is referred to as KAIST (카이스트, *Kaiseuteu*) in both English and Korean.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] The 3 most prestigious schools in Korea are known as SKY (스카이, *seukai*), combining the first letter of their English names (**S**eoul National, **K**orea, and **Y**onsei Universities).
[src:cites/acronym-p02] In addition, the College Scholastic Ability Test (대학수학능력시험, *Daehak Suhang Neungryeok Siheom*) is shortened to *Suneung* (수능, 'S.A.').
[src:cites/acronym-p02] The Japanese language makes extensive use of abbreviations, but only some of these are acronyms.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] Chinese-based words (Sino-Japanese vocabulary) use similar acronym formation to Chinese, like *Tōdai* (東大) for *Tōkyō Daigaku* (東京大学, *Tokyo University*).
[src:cites/acronym-p02] It is not always the case that the first character of each word is used, as in Saikyō for 埼京, from *Saitama* + *Tōkyō* (埼玉＋東京), which uses the second character of 東京.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] Non-Chinese foreign borrowings (gairaigo) are instead frequently abbreviated as clipped compounds, rather than acronyms, using several initial sounds.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] This is visible in katakana transcriptions of foreign words, but is also found with native words (written in hiragana).
[src:cites/acronym-p02] For example, the *Pokémon* media franchise's name originally stood for "pocket monsters" (**ポケ**ット·**モン**スター [po-ke-tto-mon-su-tā] (arrow for r) ポケモン), which is still the long-form of the name in Japanese, or "wāpuro" for "word processor" (**ワー**ド·**プロ**セッサー [wā-do-pu-ro-se-ssā] (arrow for r) ワープロ).
[src:cites/acronym-p02] To a greater degree than English, German often uses syllabic abbreviations instead of acronyms.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] Some examples are *Gestapo* rather than *GSP* (for *Geheime Staatspolizei*, 'Secret State Police'); *Flak* rather than *FAK* (for *Fliegerabwehrkanone*, 'anti-aircraft gun'); and *Kripo* rather than *KP* (for *Kriminalpolizei*, 'detective division police').
[src:cites/acronym-p02] The overuse of such contractions has been mockingly labeled *Aküfi* (for *Abkürzungsfimmel*, 'strange habit of abbreviating').
[src:cites/acronym-p02] Examples of *Aküfi* include *Vokuhila* (for *vorne kurz, hinten lang*, 'short in the front, long in the back', i.e., a mullet haircut) and the mocking of Adolf Hitler's title as *Gröfaz* (*Größter Feldherr aller Zeiten*, 'Greatest General of all Time').
[src:cites/acronym-p02] Examples (keeping in mind that Hebrew reads right-to-left): ארה״ב (for ארצות הברית, the United States); ברה״מ (for ברית המועצות, the Soviet Union); ראשל״צ (for ראשון לציון, Rishon LeZion); ביה״ס (for בית הספר, the school).
[src:cites/acronym-p02] An example that takes only the initial letters from its component words is צה״ל (*Tzahal*, for צבא הגנה לישראל, Israel Defense Forces).
[src:cites/acronym-p02] In inflected forms, the abbreviation sign *gershayim* remains between the second-last and last letters of the non-inflected form of the acronym (e.g.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] 'report', singular: דו״ח, plural: דו״חות; 'squad commander', masculine: מ״כ, feminine: מ״כית).
[src:cites/acronym-p02] There is also a widespread use of acronyms in Indonesia in every aspect of social life.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] Some acronyms are considered formal (or officially adopted), while many more are considered informal, slang, or colloquial.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] The capital's metropolitan area (Jakarta and its surrounding satellite regions), *Jabodetabek*, is another acronym.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] This stands for *Jakarta-Bogor-Depok-Tangerang-Bekasi*.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] Many highways are also named by the acronym method, e.g.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] *Jalan Tol* ('Toll Road'), *Jagorawi* (*Jakarta-Bogor-Ciawi*), *Purbaleunyi* (*Purwakarta-Bandung-Cileunyi*), and *Joglo Semar* (*Jogja-Solo-Semarang*).
[src:cites/acronym-p02] In some languages, especially those that use certain alphabets, many acronyms come from the governmental use, particularly in the military and law enforcement services.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] The Indonesian military (TNI – *Tentara Nasional Indonesia*) and Indonesian police (POLRI – *Kepolisian Republik Indonesia*) are known for heavy acronyms use.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] Although not as common as in its sister language Indonesian, a number of Malaysian (*Bahasa Malaysia*) words are formed by merging two words, such as *tadika* from *taman didikan kanak-kanak* ('kindergarten') and *pawagam* from *panggung wayang gambar*.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] This, however, has been less prevalent in the modern era, in contrary to Indonesian.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] It is still often for names such as organisation names, among the most famous being MARA from *Majlis Amanah Rakyat* ('People's Trust Council'), a government agency in Malaysia.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] Rules in writing initialisms in Malaysian differ based on its script.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] In its Latin form, the initialism would be spelt much like in English, using capitals written without any spacing, such as TNB for *Tenaga Nasional Berhad*.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] In Jawi, however, initialisms differ depending on the source language.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] For Malay initialisms, the initial Jawi letters would be written separated by a period such as د.ب.ڤ for ديوان بهاس دان ڤوستاک.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] If the initialism is from a different language, however, it would be written by transliterating each letter from the original language, such as عيم.سي.عيم.سي. for MCMC, or الفا.ڤي.ثيتا for Α.Π.Θ.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] Acronyms that use parts of words (not necessarily syllables) are commonplace in Russian as well, e.g. Газпром (*Gazprom*), for Газовая промышленность (*Gazovaya promyshlennost*, 'gas industry').
[src:cites/acronym-p02] Most commonly they are pronounced as words, unless they lack vowels, in which case they are pronounced by letters e.g. ФСБ (*ef-es-beh*, 'FSB'), США (*seh-sheh-ah*, USA).
[src:cites/acronym-p02] Some foreigh acronyms became own words, such as айти (*IT*) and пиар (*PR*).
[src:cites/acronym-p02] Historically, *OTMA* was an acronym sometimes used by the daughters of Emperor Nicholas II of Russia and his consort, Alexandra Feodorovna, as a group nickname for themselves, built from the first letter of each girl's name in the order of their births: Olga, Tatiana, Maria, and Anastasia.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] In Swahili, acronyms are common for naming organizations such as *TUKI*, which stands for *Taasisi ya Uchunguzi wa Kiswahili* ('Institute for Swahili Research').
[src:cites/acronym-p02] Multiple initial letters (often the initial syllable of words) are often drawn together, as seen more in some languages than others.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] In Vietnamese, which has an abundance of compound words, initialisms are very commonly used for both proper and common nouns.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] Longer examples include *CHXHCNVN* (*Cộng hòa Xã hội chủ nghĩa Việt Nam*, 'Socialist Republic of Vietnam') and *MTDTGPMNVN* (*Mặt trận Dân tộc Giải phóng miền Nam Việt Nam*, 'Liberation Army of South Vietnam or the National Liberation Front of South Vietnam').
[src:cites/acronym-p02] Long initialisms have become widespread in legal contexts in Vietnam, for example *TTLT-VKSNDTC-TANDTC*.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] It is also common for a writer to coin an ad hoc initialism for repeated use in an article.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] Each letter in an initialism corresponds to one morpheme, that is, one syllable.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] When the first letter of a syllable has a tone mark or other diacritic, the diacritic may be omitted from the initialism, for example *ĐNA* or *ĐNÁ* for *Đông Nam Á* ('Southeast Asia') and *LMCA* or *LMCÂ* for *Liên minh châu Âu* ('European Union').
[src:cites/acronym-p02] The letter *Ư* is often replaced by *W* in initialisms to avoid confusion with *U*, for example *UBTWMTTQVN* or *UBTƯMTTQVN* for *Ủy ban Trung ương Mặt trận Tổ quốc Việt Nam* ('Central Committee of the Vietnamese Fatherland Front').
[src:cites/acronym-p02] Initialisms are purely a written convenience, being pronounced the same way as their expansions.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] As the names of many Vietnamese letters are disyllabic, it would be less convenient to pronounce an initialism by its individual letters.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] Acronyms pronounced as words are rare in Vietnamese, occurring when an acronym itself is borrowed from another language.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] Examples include *SIĐA* (pronounced [s̪i˧ ˀɗaː˧]), a respelling of the French acronym *SIDA* ('AIDS'); *VOA* (pronounced [vwaː˧]), a literal reading of the English initialism for 'Voice of America'; and *NASA* (pronounced [naː˧ zaː˧]), borrowed directly from the English acronym.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] As in Chinese, many compound words can be shortened to the first syllable when forming a longer word.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] For example, the term *Việt Cộng* is derived from the first syllables of *Việt Nam* ('Vietnam') and *Cộng sản* ('communist').
[src:cites/acronym-p02] This mechanism is limited to Sino-Vietnamese vocabulary.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] Unlike with Chinese, such clipped compounds are considered to be portmanteau words or blend words rather than acronyms or initialisms, because the Vietnamese alphabet still requires each component word to be written as more than one character.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] In languages where nouns are declined, various methods are used.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] The process above is similar to the way that hyphens are used for clarity in English when prefixes are added to acronyms: thus *pre-NATO policy* (rather than *preNATO*).
[src:cites/acronym-p02] In languages such as Scottish Gaelic and Irish, where lenition (initial consonant mutation) is commonplace, acronyms must also be modified in situations where case and context dictate it.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] In the case of Scottish Gaelic, a lower-case *h* is often added after the initial consonant; for example, 'BBC Scotland' in the genitive case would be written as *BhBC Alba*, with the acronym pronounced *VBC*.
[src:cites/acronym-p02] Likewise, the Gaelic acronym for *telebhisean* 'television' is *TBh*, pronounced *TV*, as in English.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] It is characterised by its long prehensile trunk with two finger-like processes; a concave back; large ears which help reduce body heat; and sturdy tusks that are noticeably curved.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Its skin is grey with scanty hairs, and bending cracks which support thermoregulation by retaining water.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] The African bush elephant inhabits a variety of habitats such as forests, grasslands, woodlands, wetlands and agricultural land.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] It is a mixed herbivore feeding mostly on grasses, creepers, herbs, leaves, and bark.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] The average adult consumes about 150 kg (330 lb) of vegetation and 230 L (51 imp gal; 61 US gal) of water each day.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] It is a social animal that lives in herds of cows and their offspring.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Adult bulls usually live alone or in small bachelor groups.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] During the mating season, males undergo musth, a period of high testosterone levels and heightened aggression.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] The menstrual cycle of cows lasts three to four months, and gestation around 22 months, the longest of any mammal.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Since 2021, the African bush elephant has been listed as Endangered on the IUCN Red List.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] It is threatened foremost by habitat destruction, and in parts of its range also by poaching for meat and ivory.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Between 2003 and 2015, the illegal killing of 14,606 African bush elephants was reported by rangers across 29 range countries.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Chad is a major transit country for smuggling of ivory in West Africa, though this trend was curtailed by raising penalties for poaching and improving law enforcement.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Poaching of the elephant in the 1970–1980s were considered the largest killings in history.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] In human culture, elephants have been extensively featured in literature, folklore and media, and are most valued for their large tusks.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Today, these names are all considered synonyms.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] A genetic study based on mitogenomic analysis revealed that the African and Asian elephant genetically diverged about 7.6 million years ago.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Phylogenetic analysis of nuclear DNA from African bush and forest elephants, Asian elephants, the woolly mammoth, and the American mastodon revealed that the African bush elephant and the African forest elephant form a sister group that genetically diverged at least 1.9 million years ago.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] They are therefore considered distinct species.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Gene flow between the two species, however, might have occurred after the split.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Some authors have suggested that *L. africana* evolved from *Loxodonta atlantica*.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] The fossil record for *L. africana* is sparse.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] The earliest possible records of the species are from the Shungura Formation around Omo in Ethiopia, which are dated to the Early Pleistocene, around 2.44-2.27 million years ago.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Another possible early record is from the Kanjera site in Kenya, dating to the Middle Pleistocene, around 500,000 years ago.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Genetic analysis suggests a major population expansion between 500,000 and 100,000 years ago.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Records become more common during the Late Pleistocene, following the extinction of the last African *Palaeoloxodon* elephant species, *Palaeoloxodon jolensis*.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] The African bush elephant has grey skin with scanty hairs.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Its large ears cover the whole shoulder, and can grow as large as 2 m × 1.5 m (6 ft 7 in × 4 ft 11 in).
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Its large ears help to reduce body heat; flapping them creates air currents and exposes large blood vessels on the inner sides to increase heat loss during hot weather.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] The African bush elephant's ears are pointed and triangular shaped.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Its sturdy tusks are curved out and point forward.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Its long trunk or proboscis ends with two finger-like tips.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] The African bush elephant is the largest and heaviest living land animal.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] The largest well-measured bull, shot in Angola in 1974, is calculated to have been 3.96 m (13.0 ft) tall at the shoulder, with this individual having an estimated weight of 10.4 t (11.5 short tons).
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Elephants attain their maximum stature when they complete the fusion of long-bone epiphyses, occurring in males around the age of 40 and females around 25 years of age.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] The dental formula of the African bush elephant is 1.0.3.30.0.3.3 × 2 = 26.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] They develop six molars in each jaw quadrant that erupt at different ages and differ in size.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] The first molars grow to a size of 2 cm (0.79 in) wide by 4 cm (1.6 in) long, are worn by the age of one year and lost by the age of about 2.5 years.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] The second molars start protruding at the age of about six months, and grow to a size of 4 cm (1.6 in) wide by 7 cm (2.8 in) long and are lost by the age of 6–7 years.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] The third molars protrude at the age of about one year, grow to a size of 5.2 cm (2.0 in) wide by 14 cm (5.5 in) long, and are lost by the age of 8–10 years.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] The fourth molars show by the age of 6–7 years, grow to a size of 6.8 cm (2.7 in) wide by 17.5 cm (6.9 in) long and are lost by the age of 22–23 years.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] The dental alveoli of the fifth molars are visible by the age of 10–11 years.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] They grow to a size of 8.5 cm (3.3 in) wide by 22 cm (8.7 in) long and are worn by the age of 45–48 years.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] The dental alveoli of the last molars are visible by the age of 26–28 years.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] They grow to a size of 9.4 cm (3.7 in) wide by 31 cm (12 in) long and are well worn by the age of 65 years.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Both sexes have large, curved, maxillary incisors known as tusks that continue growing throughout their lives.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] In the wild, a large percentage of elephants experience a tusk fracture, although this is more prevalent in captivity.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] A tusk fracture of any sort usually results in serious infections, as the pulp is exposed to the elements.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] The tusks erupt when they are 1–3 years old.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Tusks grow from deciduous teeth known as tushes that develop in the upper jaw and consist of a crown, root and pulpal cavity, which are completely formed soon after birth.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] They are composed of dentin and coated with a thin layer of cementum.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Their tips bear a conical layer of enamel that is usually worn off when the elephant is five years old.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Tusks of bulls grow faster than tusks of cows.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Mean weight of tusks at the age of 60 years is 109 kg (240 lb) in bulls and 17.7 kg (39 lb) in cows.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] The longest known tusk of an African bush elephant measured 3.51 m (11.5 ft) and weighed 117 kg (258 lb).
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] The African bush elephant occurs in sub-Saharan Africa which includes Uganda, Kenya, Tanzania, Botswana, Zimbabwe, Namibia, Zambia, Angola, Malawi, Mali, Rwanda, Mozambique and South Africa.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] It moves between a variety of habitats, including subtropical and temperate forests, dry and seasonally flooded grasslands, woodlands, wetlands, and agricultural land from sea level to mountain slopes.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] In Mali and Namibia, it also inhabits desert and semi-desert areas.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Populations of African bush elephants are increasing in some areas such as the Kruger National Park, where an annual growth of 4.2% was recorded between 2003 and 2015.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] There are estimated to be at least 17,000 elephants in the park's vicinity, as of 2015–the most of any area in South Africa.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] The increase in population occurred after the discontinuation of culling in the mid-1990s.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] This large elephant population is considered a problem to both the environment and its creatures.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] As such, with the use of natural processes, conservationists aim to control the ever-growing population.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] In other places in southern Africa, the elephant population continues to increase.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Botswana in particular hosts more African bush elephants than any other country, at 130,000.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] In a 2019 study, populations were found to be steady, though the authors also noted an unusual increase in carcasses, possibly due to a new wave of poaching which was uncommon at the time.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] In East Africa there are roughly 137,000 elephants distributed across six countries in a wide array of habitats, such as grasslands and woodlands.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] They are most threatened by illegal hunting activities, such as poaching.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] In one instance, between 2006 and 2013, the population in East Africa fell by 62% due to high poaching pressures.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Tanzania (where 80% of the East African population reside) lost the most elephants, while the resident population in Somalia went locally extinct.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] South Sudan, on the other hand, experienced an increase in elephants.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Following successful conservation and governmental actions, Kenya also saw an increase in their elephant numbers.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] In Ethiopia, the African bush elephant has historically been recorded up to an elevation of 2,500 m (8,200 ft).
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] By the late 1970s, the population had declined to one herd in the Dawa River valley and one close to the Kenyan border.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] It is estimated that between the 1980s and 2010s, elephants in Ethiopia experienced a decline of around 90%–hence the endangered assessment.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] In West and Central Africa, the population of elephants are threatened, in large part due to habitat loss and fragmentation associated with rapid growth in human populations.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Elephants occur in isolated pockets throughout the region and are for the most part decreasing in number.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] The core of elephant society is the family unit, which mostly comprises several adult cows, their daughters, and their prepubertal sons.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Iain Douglas-Hamilton, who observed African bush elephants for 4.5 years in Lake Manyara National Park, coined the term 'kinship group' for two or more family units that have close ties.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] The family unit is led by a matriarch who at times also leads the kinship group.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Groups cooperate in locating food and water, in self-defense, and in caring for offspring (termed allomothering).
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Group size varies seasonally and between locations.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] In Tsavo East and Tsavo West National Parks, groups are bigger in the rainy season and areas with open vegetation.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Aerial surveys in the late 1960s to early 1970s revealed an average group size of 6.3 individuals in Uganda's Rwenzori National Park and 28.8 individuals in Chambura Game Reserve.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] In both sites, elephants aggregated during the wet season, whereas groups were smaller in the dry season.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Young bulls gradually separate from the family unit when they are between 10 and 19 years old.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] They range alone for some time or form all-male groups.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] A 2020 study highlighted the importance of old bulls for the navigation and survival of herds and raised concerns over the removal of old bulls as "currently occur[ring] in both legal trophy hunting and illegal poaching".
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] The African bush elephant has curved skin with bending cracks, which support thermoregulation by retaining water.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] These bending cracks contribute to an evaporative cooling process which helps to maintain body temperature via homeothermy regardless of air temperature.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] The African bush elephant is herbivorous.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] It is a mixed feeder, consuming both grasses as well as woody vegetation (browse), with the proportions varying wildly depending on the habitat and time of year, ranging from almost exclusively grazing to near-total browsing.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] African bush elephants' consumption of woody plants, particularly their habit of uprooting trees, has the ability to alter the local environment, transforming woodlands into grasslands.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] African bush elephants also at times consume fruit and serve as seed dispersers.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Adults can consume up to 150 kg (330 lb) of food per day.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] To supplement their diet with minerals, they congregate at mineral-rich water holes, termite mounds, and mineral licks.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Salt licks visited by elephants in the Kalahari contain high concentrations of water-soluble sodium.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Elephants drink 180–230 litres (50–60 US gal) of water daily, and seem to prefer sites where water and soil contain sodium.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] In Kruger National Park and on the shore of Lake Kariba, elephants were observed to ingest wood ash, which also contains sodium.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] African bush elephants use their trunks for tactile communication.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] When greeting, a lower ranking individual will insert the tip of its trunk into its superior's mouth.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Elephants will also stretch out their trunk toward an approaching individual they intend to greet.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Mother elephants reassure their young with touches, embraces, and rubbings with the foot, while slapping disciplines them.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] During courtship, a couple will caress and intertwine with their trunks while playing, and fighting individuals wrestle with them.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Elephant vocalisations are variations of rumbles, trumpets, squeals, and screams.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Rumbles are mainly produced for long-distance communication and cover a broad range of frequencies which are mostly below what a human can hear.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Infrasonic rumbles can travel vast distances and are important for attracting mates and scaring off rivals.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Growls are audible rumbles and happen during greetings.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] When in pain or fear, an elephant makes an open-mouthed growl known as a bellow.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Growling can escalate into a roaring when the elephant is issuing a threat.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Trumpeting is made by blowing through the trunk and signals excitement, distress, or aggression.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Juvenile elephants squeal in distress while screaming is done by adults for intimidation.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Bulls in musth experience swelling of the temporal glands and secretion of fluid, the musth fluid, which flows down their cheeks.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] They begin to dribble urine, initially as discrete drops and later in a regular stream.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] These manifestations of musth last from a few days to months, depending on the age and condition of the bull.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] When a bull has been urinating for a long time, the proximal part of the penis and the distal end of the sheath show a greenish colour, termed the 'green penis syndrome' by Joyce Poole and Cynthia Moss.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] They guard and mate with females in estrus, who stay closer to bulls in musth than to non-musth bulls.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Urinary testosterone increases during musth.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Bulls begin to experience musth by the age of 24 years.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Periods of musth are short and sporadic in young bulls up to 35 years old, lasting a few days to weeks.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Older bulls are in musth for 2–5 months every year.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Musth occurs mainly during and following the rainy season when females are in oestrus.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Bulls in musth often chase each other and are aggressive towards other bulls in musth.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] When old and high-ranking bulls in musth threaten and chase young musth bulls, either the latter leave the group or their musth ceases.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Young bulls in musth killed (and raping some) 63 mostly endangered or rare rhinoceros (of both sexes) in Hluhluwe-Umfolozi Park and Pilanesberg National Park in South Africa during the 1990s.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] This behaviour was attributed to their young age and inadequate socialisation; they were 17–25-year-old orphans from culled families who were spared due to their size and age but grew up without the guidance of either a breeding herd or dominant bulls.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] They entered musth prematurely and were rejected by older female elephants, thus leading to the assaults.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Ecologist and gamekeeper Gus Van Dyk thought of a solution after the temporary solution of shooting three young bulls suspected of massacring the rhinos.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] When six adult bulls were introduced into Pilanesberg and ten bulls were introduced into Hluhluwe-Umfolozi—each up to 45 years old—the killings stopped.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Older male elephants suppress the musth and can also control the aggressiveness of younger bulls.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Spermatogenesis starts when bulls are about 15 years old.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] However, males have not begun sexual cycles, not experiencing their first musth period until they are 25 or 30 years of age.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Cows ovulate for the first time at the age of 11 years.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] In captivity, cows have an oestrous cycle lasting 14–15 weeks.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Foetal gonads enlarge during the second half of pregnancy.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] African bush elephants mate during the rainy season.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Bulls in musth cover long distances in search of cows and associate with large family units.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] They listen for the cows' loud, very low frequency calls and attract cows by calling and by leaving trails of strong-smelling urine.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Cows search for bulls in musth, listen for their calls, and follow their urine trails.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Bulls in musth are more successful at obtaining mating opportunities than those who are not.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] A cow may move away from bulls that attempt to test her estrous condition.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] If pursued by several bulls, she will run away.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Once she chooses a mating partner, she will stay away from other bulls, which are threatened and chased away by the favoured bull.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Competition between bulls sometimes overrides the cow's choice of mating partner.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] After the mating period, females will undergo a gestation of 22 months.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] The interval between births was estimated at 3.9 to 4.7 years in Hwange National Park.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Where hunting pressure on adult elephants was high in the 1970s, cows gave birth once in 2.9 to 3.8 years.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Cows in Amboseli National Park gave birth once in 5 years on average.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] The birth of a calf was observed in Tsavo East National Park in October 1990.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] A group of 80 elephants including eight bulls had gathered in the morning in a 150 m (490 ft) radius around the birth site.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] A small group of calves and cows stood near the pregnant cow, rumbling and flapping their ears.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] While she was in labour, fluid streamed from her temporal and ear canals.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] She remained standing while giving birth.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] The newborn calf struggled to its feet within 30 minutes and walked 20 minutes later.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] The mother expelled the placenta about 100 minutes after birth and covered it with soil immediately.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Captive-born calves weigh between 100 and 120 kg (220 and 260 lb) at birth and gain about 0.5 kg (1.1 lb) weight per day.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Calves exclusively suckle their mother's milk during the first three months.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Thereafter, they start feeding independently and slowly increase the time spent feeding until they are two years old.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] During the first three years, male calves spend more time suckling and grow faster than female calves.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] After this period, cows reject male calves more frequently from nursing than female calves.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] The maximum lifespan of the African bush elephant is between 70 and 75 years.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Adult elephants are considered invulnerable to predation.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Adult elephants often chase off predators, especially lions, by mobbing behaviour.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Calves, usually under two years, are sometimes preyed on by lions and spotted hyenas.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Juveniles are usually well defended by protective adults though serious drought makes them vulnerable to lion predation.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] In Botswana's Chobe National Park, lions attacked and fed on juvenile and subadult elephants during the drought when smaller prey species were scarce.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Between 1993 and 1996, lions successfully attacked 74 elephants; 26 were older than nine, and one was a bull of over 15 years.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Most were killed at night, and hunts occurred more often during waning moon nights than during bright moon nights.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] In the same park, lions killed eight elephants in October 2005 that were aged between 1 and 11 years, two of them older than 8 years.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Successful hunts took place after dark when prides exceeded 27 lions and herds were smaller than 5 elephants.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Observations at Etosha National Park indicate that African bush elephants die due to anthrax foremost in November at the end of the dry season.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Anthrax spores spread through the intestinal tracts of vultures, jackals and hyaenas that feed on the carcasses.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Anthrax killed over 100 elephants in Botswana in 2019.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] It is thought that wild bush elephants can contract fatal tuberculosis from humans.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Infection of the vital organs by *Citrobacter freundii* bacteria caused the death of an otherwise healthy bush elephant after capture and translocation.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] From April to June 2020, over 400 bush elephants died in Botswana's Okavango Delta region after drinking from desiccating waterholes that were infested with cyanobacteria.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Neurotoxins produced by the cyanobacteria caused calves and adult elephants to wander around confused, emaciated and in distress.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] The elephants collapsed when the toxin impaired their motor functions and their legs became paralysed.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Poaching, intentional poisoning, and anthrax were excluded as potential causes.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Elephants may also be host for a variety of parasites and bacteria such as *Pasteurella*, *Salmonella*, *Clostridium,* coccidian, nematode, and *trematode*.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] The elephant endotheliotropic herpesvirus (EEHV) is a member of the *Proboscivirus* genus, a novel clade most closely related to the mammalian betaherpesviruses.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] In benign infections found in some wild and captive African elephants, these viruses can affect either the skin or the pulmonary system.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Both African and Asian elephants have a very large and highly complex neocortex, a trait also shared by humans, apes and certain dolphin species.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Elephants manifest a wide variety of behaviour, including those associated with grief, learning, mimicry, playing, altruism, tool use, compassion, cooperation, self-awareness, memory, and communication.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] In a 2013 study, it was suggested that elephants may understand pointing, the ability to nonverbally communicate an object by extending a finger, or equivalent.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] The intelligence of elephants is described as being on a par with that of cetaceans, and various primates.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] The African bush elephant is threatened primarily by habitat loss and fragmentation following conversion of natural habitat for livestock farming, plantations of non-timber crops, and building of urban and industrial areas.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] As a result, human-elephant conflict has increased.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Poachers target foremost elephant bulls for their tusks, which leads to a skewed sex ratio and affects the survival chances of a population.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Access of poachers to unregulated black markets is facilitated by corruption and periods of civil war in some elephant range countries.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] During the 20th century, the African bush elephant population was decimated.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Poaching of the elephant has dated back to the years 1970 and 1980, which were considered the largest killings in history.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] The species is placed in harm's way due to the limited conservation areas provided in Africa.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] In most cases, the killings of the African bush elephant have occurred near the outskirts of the protected areas.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Chad is a major transit country for smuggling of ivory in West Africa.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] This trend was curtailed by raising penalties for poaching and improving law enforcement.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Before this in June 2002, a container packed with more than 6.5 t (6.4 long tons; 7.2 short tons) ivory was confiscated in Singapore.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] It contained 42,120 hanko stamps and 532 tusks of African bush elephants that originated in Southern Africa, centred in Zambia and neighboring countries.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Between 2005 and 2006, a total of 23.461 t (23.090 long tons; 25.861 short tons) ivory plus 91 unweighed tusks of African bush elephants were confiscated in 12 major consignments being shipped to Asia.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] When the international ivory trade reopened in 2006, the demand and price for ivory increased in Asia.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] The African bush elephant population in Chad's Zakouma National Park numbered 3,900 individuals in 2005.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Within five years, more than 3,200 elephants were killed.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] The park did not have sufficient guards to combat poaching, and their weapons were outdated.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Well-organised networks facilitated smuggling the ivory through Sudan.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Poaching also increased in Kenya in those years.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] In Samburu National Reserve, 41 bulls were illegally killed between 2008 and 2012, equivalent to 31% of the reserve's elephant population.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] These killings were linked to confiscations of ivory and increased prices for ivory on the local black market.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] About 10,370 tusks were confiscated in Singapore, Hong Kong, Taiwan, Philippines, Thailand, Malaysia, Kenya and Uganda between 2007 and 2013.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Genetic analysis of tusk samples showed that they originated from African bush elephants killed in Tanzania, Mozambique, Zambia, Kenya, and Uganda.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Most of the ivory was smuggled through East African countries.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] In addition to elephants being poached, their carcasses may be poisoned by the poachers to avoid detection by vultures, which help rangers detect poaching activity by circling dead animals.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] This poses a threat to those vultures or birds that scavenge the carcasses.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Intensive poaching leads to strong selection on tusk attributes; African elephants in areas with heavy poaching often have smaller tusks and a higher frequency of congenitally tuskless females, whereas congenital tusklessness is rarely if ever observed in males.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] A study in Mozambique's Gorongosa National Park revealed that poaching during the Mozambican Civil War led to the increasing birth of tuskless females when the population recovered.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Vast areas in Sub-Saharan Africa were transformed for agricultural use and the building of infrastructure.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] This disturbance leaves the elephants without a stable habitat and limits their ability to roam freely.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Large corporations associated with commercial logging and mining have fragmented the land, giving poachers easy access to the African bush elephants.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] As human development grows, the human population faces the trouble of contact with the elephants more frequently, due to the species need for food and water.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Farmers residing in nearby areas come into conflict with the African bush elephants rummaging through their crops.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] In many cases, they kill the elephants as soon as they disturb a village or forage upon its crops.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Deaths caused by browsing on rubber vine, an invasive plant, have also been reported.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Both African elephant species have been listed on Appendix I of the Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species of Wild Fauna and Flora since 1989.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] In 1997, populations of Botswana, Namibia, and Zimbabwe were placed on CITES Appendix II, as were populations of South Africa in 2000.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Community-based conservation programmes have been initiated in several range countries, which contributed to reducing human-elephant conflict and increasing local people's tolerance towards elephants.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Researchers discovered that playing back the recorded sounds of African bees is an effective method to drive elephants away from settlements.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] In 1986, the African Elephant Database was initiated to collate and update information on the distribution and status of elephant populations in Africa.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] The database includes results from aerial surveys, dung counts, interviews with local people, and data on poaching.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] In 2008, the IUCN Red List assessed the African elephant (then considered as a single species) as vulnerable.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Since 2021, the African bush elephant has individually been assessed Endangered, after the global population was found to have decreased by more than 50% over 3 generations.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] More than 50% of its range is located outside protected areas.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] In 2016, the global population was estimated at 415,428 ± 20,111 individuals distributed in a total area of 20,731,202 km2 (8,004,362 sq mi), of which 30% is protected.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Approximately 42% of the total population lives in nine southern African countries comprising 293,447 ± 16,682 individuals; Africa's largest population lives in Botswana with 131,626 ± 12,508 individuals.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] The social behaviour of elephants in captivity mimics that of those in the wild.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Cows are kept with other cows, in groups, while bulls tend to be separated from their mothers at a young age and are kept apart.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] According to Schulte, in the 1990s, in North America, a few facilities allowed bull interaction.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Elsewhere, bulls were only allowed to smell each other.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Bulls and cows were allowed to interact for specific purposes such as breeding.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] In that event, cows were more often moved to the bull than the bull to the cow.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Cows are more often kept in captivity because they are easier and less expensive to house.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] In Africa, elephants have found a prominent role in human culture since ancient times and were most priced for their ivory tusks, which were considered valuable commercial goods.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] In Kenya, the Maasai people have been known to use elephants for their tusks and often regard them as akin to humans.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] They feature extensively in Maasai culture, going by the local name of *Arkanjowe* (a being that is large and/or powerful).
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] According to a Maasai legend, the elephant came to be when a woman, who was on her way to her partner's place for marriage, turned her back before reaching the destination.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] This event caused the woman to shape-shift into an elephant.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] Prehistoric North Africans depicted the elephant in Paleolithic age rock art.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] For example, the Libyan Tadrart Acacus, a UNESCO World Heritage Site, features a rock carving of an elephant from the last phase of the Pleistocene epoch (12,000–8000 BC) rendered with remarkable realism.
[src:cites/african-bush-elephant] There are many other prehistoric examples, including Neolithic rock art of south Oran (Algeria), and a white elephant rock painting in 'Phillip's Cave' by the San in the Erongo region of Namibia.
[src:cites/african-civet] The **African civet** (***Civettictis civetta***) is a large viverrid native to sub-Saharan Africa, where it is considered common and widely distributed in woodlands and secondary forests.
[src:cites/african-civet] It has been listed as least concern on the IUCN Red List since 2008.
[src:cites/african-civet] In some countries, it is threatened by hunting, and wild-caught individuals are kept for producing civetone for the perfume industry.
[src:cites/african-civet] The African civet is primarily nocturnal and spends the day sleeping in dense vegetation, but wakes up at sunset.
[src:cites/african-civet] It is a solitary mammal with a unique coloration: the black and white blotches covering its coarse pelage and rings on the tail are an effective cryptic pattern.
[src:cites/african-civet] The black bands surrounding its eyes closely resemble those of the raccoon.
[src:cites/african-civet] Other distinguishing features are its disproportionately large hindquarters and its erectile dorsal crest.
[src:cites/african-civet] It is an omnivorous generalist, preying on small vertebrates, invertebrates, eggs, carrion, and vegetable matter.
[src:cites/african-civet] It is one of the few carnivores capable of eating toxic invertebrates such as termites and millipedes.
[src:cites/african-civet] It detects prey primarily by smell and sound rather than by sight.
[src:cites/african-civet] It is the only living member of the genus ***Civettictis***.
[src:cites/african-civet] A 1969 study noted that this civet showed enough differences from the rest of the viverrines in terms of dentition to be classified under its own genus.
[src:cites/african-civet] A 2006 phylogenetic study showed that the African civet is closely related to the genus *Viverra*.
[src:cites/african-civet] It was estimated that the *Civettictis*-*Viverra* clade diverged from *Viverricula* around 16.2Mya; the African civet split from *Viverra* 12.3Mya.
[src:cites/african-civet] The authors suggested that the subfamily Viverrinae should be bifurcated into Genettinae (*Poiana* and *Genetta*) and Viverrinae (*Civettictis*, *Viverra,* and *Viverricula*).
[src:cites/african-civet] The following cladogram is based on this study.
[src:cites/african-civet] The generic name *Civettictis* is a fusion of the French word *civette* and the Greek word *ictis*, meaning "weasel".
[src:cites/african-civet] The specific name *civetta* and the common name "civet" come from the French *civette* or the Arabic *zabād* or *sinnawr al-zabād* ("civet cat").
[src:cites/african-civet] The African civet has a coarse and wiry fur that varies in colour from white to creamy yellow to reddish on the back.
[src:cites/african-civet] The stripes, spots, and blotches are deep brown to black.
[src:cites/african-civet] Horizontal lines are prominent on the hind limbs, spots are normally present on its midsection and fade into vertical stripes above the forelimbs.
[src:cites/african-civet] Its muzzle is pointed, ears small and rounded.
[src:cites/african-civet] A black band stretches across its small eyes, and two black bands are around its short broad neck.
[src:cites/african-civet] Following the spine of the animal extending from the neck to the base of the tail is the erectile dorsal crest.
[src:cites/african-civet] The hairs of the erectile crest are longer than those of the rest of the pelage.
[src:cites/african-civet] The sagittal crest of its skull is well-developed providing a large area for attachment of the temporal muscle.
[src:cites/african-civet] The zygomatic arch is robust and provides a large area for attachment of the masseter muscle.
[src:cites/african-civet] This musculature and its strong mandible give it a powerful bite.
[src:cites/african-civet] Its black paws are compact with hairless soles, five digits per manus in which the first toe is slightly set back from the others.
[src:cites/african-civet] Its long, curved claws are semi-retractile.
[src:cites/african-civet] The average weight is 11 to 15 kg (24 to 33 lb) within a range of 7 to 20 kg (15 to 44 lb).
[src:cites/african-civet] Only the binturong is likely heavier among the world's viverrids.
[src:cites/african-civet] Its shoulder height averages 40 cm (16 in).
[src:cites/african-civet] Both male and female have perineal and anal glands, which are bigger in males.
[src:cites/african-civet] The perineal glands are located between the scrotum and the penis in males, and between the anus and the vulva in females.
[src:cites/african-civet] African civets typically sleep during the day in the tall grasses near water sources in central and southern Africa.
[src:cites/african-civet] It often inhabits savannahs, forests, and sometimes near rivers as the tall grasses and thickets present provide them with necessary cover during the day.
[src:cites/african-civet] In Guinea's National Park of Upper Niger, it was recorded during surveys conducted in 1996 to 1997.
[src:cites/african-civet] In Gabon's Moukalaba-Doudou National Park, it was photographed close to forested areas during a survey in 2012.
[src:cites/african-civet] In Batéké Plateau National Park, it was recorded in gallery forest along the Mpassa River during surveys conducted between June 2014 and May 2015.
[src:cites/african-civet] In the Republic of Congo, it was recorded in the Western Congolian forest–savanna mosaic of Odzala-Kokoua National Park during surveys in 2007.
[src:cites/african-civet] In the transboundary Dinder–Alatash (Sudan and Ethiopia) protected area complex it was recorded during surveys between 2015 and 2018.
[src:cites/african-civet] It is also frequently spotted in Ethiopia's northern Degua Tembien massif.
[src:cites/african-civet] African civets deposit their feces in large piles called latrines, or specifically "civetries".
[src:cites/african-civet] The latrines are characterized by fruits, seeds, exoskeletons of insect and millipede rings, and occasionally clumps of grass.
[src:cites/african-civet] The role of civet latrines as a mechanism of seed dispersal and forest regeneration is still being researched.
[src:cites/african-civet] Like felids, male African civets scent mark by spraying urine backwards.
[src:cites/african-civet] African civets are typically solitary creatures.
[src:cites/african-civet] They use their perineal gland secretion to mark their territories around their civetries.
[src:cites/african-civet] These markings typically follow common routes and paths and lie within 100 meters of civetries 96.72% of the time.
[src:cites/african-civet] If an African civet feels threatened, it raises its dorsal crest to make itself look larger and thus more formidable and dangerous to attack.
[src:cites/african-civet] Research in southeastern Nigeria revealed that the African civet has an omnivorous diet.
[src:cites/african-civet] African civets can take prey as large as hares but can be somewhat clumsy killers with sizable prey.
[src:cites/african-civet] Stomach content of three African civets in Botswana included foremost husks of fan palm (*Hyphaene petersiana*) and jackalberry (*Diospyros mespiliformis*), and some remains of African red toad (*Schismaderma carens*), Acrididae grasshoppers and larvae of Dytiscidae beetles.
[src:cites/african-civet] Green grass is also frequently found in feces, and this seems to be linked to the eating of snakes and amphibians.
[src:cites/african-civet] In Southern Africa, African civets probably mate from October to November, and females give birth in the rainy season between January and February.
[src:cites/african-civet] The average lifespan of a captive African civet is 15 to 20 years.
[src:cites/african-civet] Females create a nest which is normally in dense vegetation and commonly in a hole dug by another animal.
[src:cites/african-civet] Female African civets normally give birth to one to four young.
[src:cites/african-civet] The young are born in advanced stages compared to most carnivores.
[src:cites/african-civet] They are covered in a dark, short fur and can crawl at birth.
[src:cites/african-civet] The young leave the nest after 18 days but are still dependent on the mother for milk and protection for another two months.
[src:cites/african-civet] In 2006, it was estimated that about 9,400 African civets are hunted yearly in the Nigerian part and more than 5,800 in the Cameroon part of the Cross–Sanaga–Bioko coastal forests.
[src:cites/african-civet] Skins and skulls of African civets were found in 2007 at the Dantokpa Market in southern Benin, where it was among the most expensive small carnivores.
[src:cites/african-civet] Local hunters considered it a rare species, indicating that the population declined due to hunting for trade as bushmeat.
[src:cites/african-civet] The African civet has historically been hunted for the secretion of perineal glands.
[src:cites/african-civet] This secretion is a white or yellow waxy substance called civetone, which has been used as a basic ingredient for many perfumes for hundreds of years.
[src:cites/african-civet] In Ethiopia, African civets are hunted alive, and are kept in small cages.
[src:cites/african-civet] Most die within three weeks after capture, most likely due to stress.
[src:cites/african-civet] Extraction of the civetone is cruel and has been criticised by animal rights activists.
[src:cites/african-civet] The writer Daniel Defoe once invested in a scheme to raise civets in captivity for their secretions.
[src:cites/african-civet] The population of African civet in Botswana is listed under Appendix III of the Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species of Wild Fauna and Flora (CITES).
[src:cites/african-elephant] Both species are at risk of extinction according to the IUCN Red List; as of 2021, the bush elephant is considered endangered while the forest elephant is considered critically endangered.
[src:cites/african-elephant] They are threatened by habitat loss and fragmentation, along with poaching for the illegal ivory trade in several range countries.
[src:cites/african-elephant] The name *Loxodonta* comes from the Ancient Greek words λοξός (*loxós,*"slanting", "crosswise") and ὀδούς (*odoús*, "tooth"), referring to the lozenge-shaped enamel of the molar teeth, which differs significantly from the rounded shape of the Asian elephant's molar enamel.
[src:cites/african-elephant] The first scientific description of the African elephant was written in 1797 by Johann Friedrich Blumenbach, who proposed the scientific name *Elephas africanus*.
[src:cites/african-elephant] *Loxodonte* was proposed as a generic name for the African elephant by Frédéric Cuvier in 1825.
[src:cites/african-elephant] An anonymous author used the Latinized spelling *Loxodonta* in 1827.
[src:cites/african-elephant] This author was recognized as authority by the International Code of Zoological Nomenclature in 1999.
[src:cites/african-elephant] In 1907, Richard Lydekker proposed six African elephant subspecies based on the different sizes and shapes of their ears.
[src:cites/african-elephant] They are all considered synonymous with the African bush elephant.
[src:cites/african-elephant] A third species, the West African elephant, has also been proposed but needs confirmation.
[src:cites/african-elephant] It is thought that this lineage has been isolated from the others for 2.4 million years.
[src:cites/african-elephant] Relationships of living and extinct elephants based on DNA, after Palkopoulou et al.
[src:cites/african-elephant] The oldest species of *Loxodonta* known is *Loxodonta cookei,* with remains of the species known from around 7–5 million years ago, from remains found in Chad, Kenya, Uganda, and South Africa.
[src:cites/african-elephant] Analysis of nuclear DNA sequences indicates that the genetic divergence between African bush and forest elephants dates 2.6 – 5.6 million years ago.
[src:cites/african-elephant] The African forest elephant was found to have a high degree of genetic diversity, likely reflecting periodic fragmentation of their habitat during the changes in the Pleistocene.
[src:cites/african-elephant] Gene flow between the two African elephant species was examined at 21 locations.
[src:cites/african-elephant] The analysis revealed that several African bush elephants carried mitochondrial DNA of African forest elephants, indicating they hybridised in the savanna-forest transition zone in ancient times.
[src:cites/african-elephant] However, despite the hybridisation at the contact zone between the two species, there appears to have been little effective gene flow between the two species since their initial split.
[src:cites/african-elephant] DNA from the European straight-tusked elephant (*Palaeoloxodon antiquus*) indicates that the extinct elephant genus *Palaeoloxodon* is more closely related to African elephants than to Asian elephants or mammoths.
[src:cites/african-elephant] Analysis of Chinese *Palaeoloxodon* mitogenomes suggests that this forest elephant ancestry was widely shared among *Palaeoloxodon* species.
[src:cites/african-elephant] African elephants have grey folded skin up to 30 mm (1.2 in) thick that is covered with sparse, bristled dark-brown to black hair.
[src:cites/african-elephant] Short tactile hair grows on the trunk, which has two finger-like processes at the tip, whereas Asian elephants only have one.
[src:cites/african-elephant] Their large ears help to reduce body heat.
[src:cites/african-elephant] Flapping them creates air currents and exposes the ears' inner sides where large blood vessels increase heat loss during hot weather.
[src:cites/african-elephant] The trunk is a prehensile elongation of its upper lip and nose.
[src:cites/african-elephant] This highly sensitive organ is innervated primarily by the trigeminal nerve, and is thought to be manipulated by about 40,000–60,000 muscles.
[src:cites/african-elephant] Because of this muscular structure, the trunk is so strong that elephants can use it to lift about 3% of their own body weight.
[src:cites/african-elephant] They use it for smelling, touching, feeding, drinking, dusting, producing sounds, loading, defending and attacking.
[src:cites/african-elephant] Elephants sometimes swim underwater and use their trunks as snorkels.
[src:cites/african-elephant] Both male and female African elephants have tusks that grow from deciduous teeth called tushes, which are replaced by tusks when calves are about one year old.
[src:cites/african-elephant] Tusks are composed of dentin, which forms small diamond-shaped structures in the tusk's center that become larger at its periphery.
[src:cites/african-elephant] Tusks are primarily used to dig for roots and strip the bark from trees for food, for fighting each other during the mating season, and for defending themselves against predators.
[src:cites/african-elephant] The tusks weigh from 23 to 45 kg (51–99 lb) and can be from 1.5 to 2.4 m (5–8 ft) long.
[src:cites/african-elephant] They are curved forward and continue to grow throughout the elephant's lifetime.
[src:cites/african-elephant] Elephants have four molars; each weighs about 5 kg (11 lb) and measures about 30 cm (12 in) long.
[src:cites/african-elephant] As the front pair wears down and drops out in pieces, the back pair moves forward, and two new molars emerge in the back of the mouth.
[src:cites/african-elephant] Elephants replace their teeth four to six times in their lifetimes.
[src:cites/african-elephant] At around 40 to 60 years of age, the elephant loses the last of its molars and will likely die of starvation which is a common cause of death.
[src:cites/african-elephant] African elephants have 24 teeth in total, six on each quadrant of the jaw.
[src:cites/african-elephant] The enamel plates of the molars are fewer in number than in Asian elephants.
[src:cites/african-elephant] The enamel of the molar teeth wears into a distinctive lozenge/loxodont (**<>**) shape characteristic to all members of the genus *Loxodonta*.
[src:cites/african-elephant] While some extinct species of *Loxodonta* retained permanent premolar teeth, these have been lost in both living species.
[src:cites/african-elephant] The African bush elephant is the largest terrestrial animal.
[src:cites/african-elephant] The largest recorded bull stood 3.96 m (13.0 ft) at the shoulder and is estimated to have weighed 10.4 t (10.2 long tons; 11.5 short tons).
[src:cites/african-elephant] Its back is concave-shaped, while the back of the African forest elephant is nearly straight.
[src:cites/african-elephant] The African forest elephant is considerably smaller.
[src:cites/african-elephant] Fully grown African forest elephant males in optimal conditions where individuals are capable of reaching full growth potential are estimated to be on average 2.09–2.31 m (6.9–7.6 ft) tall and 1.7–2.3 t (1.7–2.3 long tons; 1.9–2.5 short tons) in weight.
[src:cites/african-elephant] African elephants are distributed in Sub-Saharan Africa, where they inhabit Sahelian scrubland and arid regions, tropical rainforests, mopane and miombo woodlands.
[src:cites/african-elephant] African forest elephant populations occur only in Central and West Africa.
[src:cites/african-elephant] Both African elephant species live in family units comprising several adult cows, their daughters and their subadult sons.
[src:cites/african-elephant] Each family unit is led by an older cow known as the matriarch.
[src:cites/african-elephant] African forest elephant groups are less cohesive than African bush elephant groups, probably due to the lack of natural predators.
[src:cites/african-elephant] When separate family units bond, they form kinship or bond groups.
[src:cites/african-elephant] After puberty, male elephants tend to form close alliances with other males.
[src:cites/african-elephant] While females are the most active members of African elephant groups, both male and female elephants are capable of distinguishing between hundreds of different low-frequency infrasonic calls to communicate with and identify each other.
[src:cites/african-elephant] Elephants use some vocalisations that are beyond the hearing range of humans, to communicate across large distances.
[src:cites/african-elephant] Elephant mating rituals include the gentle entwining of trunks.
[src:cites/african-elephant] Bulls were believed to be solitary animals, becoming independent once reaching maturity.
[src:cites/african-elephant] New research suggests that bulls maintain ecological knowledge for the herd, facilitating survival when searching for food and water, which also benefits the young bulls who associate with them.
[src:cites/african-elephant] Bulls only return to the herd to breed or to socialize; they do not provide parental care to their offspring or raise them, but rather play a fatherly role in general to younger bulls to show dominance.
[src:cites/african-elephant] African elephants are not strictly territorial but they display various types of patterns of space use which are influenced by social structure, seasonal and climate variation, and resource availability.
[src:cites/african-elephant] Additional factors such as social dominance and environmental factors like rainfall and vegetation productivity also influences spatial segregation among groups within the same region.
[src:cites/african-elephant] African elephants displays complex patterns of aggression accompanied with dominance, especially within adult males.
[src:cites/african-elephant] Musth is a term which refers to physiological state where male African elephants exhibit massive surges of testosterone, heightened sexual activity, and increased aggression and is observed during male - male competition.
[src:cites/african-elephant] During the period where male African elephant undergo musth, they display characteristic behavior which includes temporal gland secretion, urine dribbling, and certain postures which explains their condition to other individuals.
[src:cites/african-elephant] By performing these behaviors, male African elephants reduces the need for physical confrontation by communicating dominance status.
[src:cites/african-elephant] However, in cases where these type of communication fails, aggressive encounters including tusking and pushing may occur when competing for receptive females.
[src:cites/african-elephant] The dominance hierarchy within a herd of elephants are largely influenced and based on age, size, and musth status with older males typically outcompeting younger or non-musth individuals.
[src:cites/african-elephant] African elephants are generalist herbivores and consume a wide variety of leaves, grasses, bark, and fruits, but woody vegetation in dry seasons.
[src:cites/african-elephant] While feeding, they pluck leaves and tear at branches using tusks, which can cause enormous damage to foliage.
[src:cites/african-elephant] Fermentation of the food takes place in the hindgut, enabling large food intakes.
[src:cites/african-elephant] The large size and hindgut of the African elephant also allows for the digestion of various plant parts, including fibrous stems, bark and roots.
[src:cites/african-elephant] African elephants aid in germination of seeds thanks to their large stomachs; as they are able to cover a large area within one day, they spread seeds from different trees rapidly.
[src:cites/african-elephant] The elephants graze on the trees and consume seeds from them, and then, with the seed passing through the gastrointestinal tract and then secreted out, the seeds are fertilized and ready to grow.
[src:cites/african-elephant] The germination via elephants prevents plant competition and removes the requirement for some seeds to be wind-blown to grow, or the process of random germination.
[src:cites/african-elephant] The diversity of plants and trees that can grow through this process also increases because the dung piles can contain upwards of 10 different tree species, with some containing traces of 50 trees and above.
[src:cites/african-elephant] African elephants are highly intelligent.
[src:cites/african-elephant] They have a very large and highly convoluted neocortex, a trait they share with humans and other apes, as well as some dolphin species.
[src:cites/african-elephant] They are among the world's most intelligent species.
[src:cites/african-elephant] With a mass of just over 5 kg (11 lb), the elephant brain is larger than that of any other terrestrial animal.
[src:cites/african-elephant] The elephant's brain is similar to a human brain in terms of structure and complexity; the elephant's cortex has as many neurons as that of a human brain, suggesting convergent evolution.
[src:cites/african-elephant] Elephants exhibit a wide variety of behaviours, including those associated with grief, learning, mimicry, art, play, a sense of humor, altruism, use of tools, compassion, cooperation, self-awareness, memory and possibly language.
[src:cites/african-elephant] All of these behaviors point to a highly intelligent species that is thought to be equal to cetaceans and primates.
[src:cites/african-elephant] The African elephant's cognitive complexity includes behaviors indicative of empathy, problem-solving, and cooperative group behaviors.
[src:cites/african-elephant] These traits underscore the evolutionary convergence of intelligence across species, similar to that seen in primates and cetaceans.
[src:cites/african-elephant] African elephants are at their most fertile between the ages of 25 and 45 years.
[src:cites/african-elephant] Calves are normally born after a gestation period of 22 months.
[src:cites/african-elephant] The calves are cared for by their mother and other young females in the group, known as allomothering.
[src:cites/african-elephant] Female African elephants are able to start reproducing at around 10 to 12 years of age.
[src:cites/african-elephant] Post sexual maturity, males begin to experience musth, a physical and behavioral condition that is characterized by elevated testosterone, aggression and more sexual activity.
[src:cites/african-elephant] Musth also serves a purpose of calling attention to the females that they are of good quality, and it cannot be mimicked as certain calls or noises may be.
[src:cites/african-elephant] Males sire few offspring in periods when they are not in musth.
[src:cites/african-elephant] During the middle of estrus, female elephants look for males in musth to guard them.
[src:cites/african-elephant] The females will yell, in a loud, low way to attract males from far away.
[src:cites/african-elephant] Male elephants can also smell the hormones of a female ready for breeding.
[src:cites/african-elephant] This leads males to compete with each other to mate, which results in the females mating with older, healthier males.
[src:cites/african-elephant] Females choose to a point who they mate with, since they are the ones who try to get males to compete to guard them.
[src:cites/african-elephant] However, females are not guarded in the early and late stages of estrus, which may permit mating by younger males not in musth.
[src:cites/african-elephant] Males over the age of 25 compete strongly for females in estrus, and are more successful the larger and more aggressive they are.
[src:cites/african-elephant] Bigger males tend to sire bigger offspring.
[src:cites/african-elephant] Wild males begin breeding in their thirties when they are at a size and weight that is competitive with other adult males.
[src:cites/african-elephant] Male reproductive success is maximal in mid-adulthood and then begins to decline.
[src:cites/african-elephant] However, this can depend on the ranking of the male within their group, as higher-ranking males maintain a higher rate of reproduction.
[src:cites/african-elephant] Most observed matings are by males in musth over 35 years of age.
[src:cites/african-elephant] Both species are threatened by habitat loss and fragmentation.
[src:cites/african-elephant] Poaching for the illegal ivory trade is a threat in several range countries as well.
[src:cites/african-elephant] The African bush elephant is listed as Endangered and the African forest elephant as Critically Endangered on the respective IUCN Red Lists.
[src:cites/african-elephant] Based on vegetation types that provide suitable habitat for African elephants, it was estimated that in the early 19th century a maximum of 26,913,000 African elephants might have been present from the Sahel in the north to the Highveld in the south.
[src:cites/african-elephant] Decrease of suitable habitat was the major cause for the decline of elephant populations until the 1950s.
[src:cites/african-elephant] Hunting African elephants for the ivory trade accelerated the decline from the 1970s onwards.
[src:cites/african-elephant] The carrying capacity of remaining suitable habitats was estimated at 8,985,000 elephants at most by 1987.
[src:cites/african-elephant] In the 1970s and 1980s, the price of ivory rose, and poaching for ivory increased, particularly in Central African range countries where access to elephant habitats was facilitated by logging and petroleum mining industries.
[src:cites/african-elephant] Between 1976 and 1980, about 830 t (820 long tons; 910 short tons) raw ivory was exported from Africa to Hong Kong and Japan, equivalent to tusks of about 222,000 African elephants.
[src:cites/african-elephant] The first continental elephant census was carried out in 1976.
[src:cites/african-elephant] At the time, 1.34 million elephants were estimated to range over 7,300,000 km2 (2,800,000 sq mi).
[src:cites/african-elephant] In the 1980s, it was difficult to carry out systematic surveys in several East African range countries due to civil wars.
[src:cites/african-elephant] In 1987, it was estimated that the African elephant population had declined to 760,000 individuals.
[src:cites/african-elephant] In 1989, only 608,000 African elephants were estimated to have survived.
[src:cites/african-elephant] In 1989, the Kenyan Wildlife Service burned a stockpile of tusks in protest against the ivory trade.
[src:cites/african-elephant] In Chad's Zakouma National Park, more than 3,200 elephants were killed between 2005 and 2010.
[src:cites/african-elephant] The park did not have sufficient guards to combat poaching and their weapons were outdated.
[src:cites/african-elephant] Well organized networks facilitated smuggling the ivory through Sudan.
[src:cites/african-elephant] The government of Tanzania estimated that more than 85,000 elephants were lost to poaching in Tanzania between 2009 and 2014, representing a 60% loss.
[src:cites/african-elephant] In 2012, a large upsurge in ivory poaching was reported, with about 70% of the product flowing to China.
[src:cites/african-elephant] China was the biggest market for poached ivory but announced that it would phase out the legal domestic manufacture and sale of ivory products in May 2015.
[src:cites/african-elephant] Conflicts between elephants and a growing human population are a major issue in elephant conservation.
[src:cites/african-elephant] Human encroachment into natural areas where bush elephants occur or their increasing presence in adjacent areas has spurred research into methods of safely driving groups of elephants away from humans.
[src:cites/african-elephant] Playback of the recorded sounds of angry Western honey bees has been found to be remarkably effective at prompting elephants to flee an area.
[src:cites/african-elephant] Farmers have tried scaring elephants away by more aggressive means such as fire or the use of chili peppers along fences to protect their crops.
[src:cites/african-elephant] The main threats to African elephants are habitat loss and poaching, in addition to these main, most concerning threats, more recent threats emerged which includes human-made barriers and landscape modification which significantly affect and limits African elephant movement and distribution.
[src:cites/african-elephant] Construction of fences, roads, artificial water points, and agricultural lands have reported severe impact in altering natural movement patterns, fragmenting habitats, and limiting access to seasonal resources.
[src:cites/african-elephant] In 1986, the African Elephant Database was initiated with the aim to monitor the status of African elephant populations.
[src:cites/african-elephant] This database includes results from aerial surveys, dung counts, interviews with local people and data on poaching.
[src:cites/african-elephant] In 1989, the Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species of Wild Fauna and Flora listed the African elephant on CITES Appendix I.
[src:cites/african-elephant] This listing banned international trade of African elephants and their body parts by countries that signed the CITES agreement.
[src:cites/african-elephant] Hunting elephants is banned in the Central African Republic, Democratic Republic of Congo, Gabon, Côte d'Ivoire, and Senegal.
[src:cites/african-elephant] After the ban came into force in 1990, retail sales of ivory carvings in South Africa have plummeted by more than 95% within 10 years.
[src:cites/african-elephant] As a result of the trade ban, African elephant populations recovered in Southern African range countries.
[src:cites/african-elephant] The African Elephant Specialist Group has set up a *Human-Elephant Conflict Task Force* with the aim to develop conflict mitigation strategies.
[src:cites/african-elephant] In 2005, the West African Elephant Memorandum of Understanding was signed by 12 West African countries.
[src:cites/african-elephant] The Convention on the Conservation of Migratory Species of Wild Animals provided financial support for four years to implement the West African Elephant Conservation Strategy, which forms the central component of this intergovernmental treaty.
[src:cites/african-elephant] In 2019, the export of wild African elephants to zoos around the world was banned, with an exception added by the EU to allow export in "exceptional cases where … it is considered that a transfer to ex-situ locations will provide demonstrable in-situ conservation benefits for African elephants".
[src:cites/african-elephant] Previously, export had been allowed in Southern Africa with Zimbabwe capturing and exporting more than 100 baby elephants to Chinese zoos since 2012.
[src:cites/african-elephant] It was found that elephant conservation does not pose a trade-off with climate change mitigation.
[src:cites/african-elephant] Although animals typically cause a reduction of woody biomass and therewith above-ground carbon, they foster soil carbon sequestration.
[src:cites/african-elephant] Recent conservation approaches for African elephants are more focused on territorial-level management and the maintenance of ecological connectivity between fragmented areas where artificial causes are the main factor influencing African elephant population.
[src:cites/african-elephant] By interpreting on migration corridors and by sustaining connection between protected areas, it would support natural movement patterns and balanced access to seasonal resources.
[src:cites/african-elephant] Conservation strategies will include efforts to weaken the impacts of human infrastructure such as removal of fences and improved land use planning which would propose to reduce habitat fragmentation and human elephant conflict.
[src:cites/african-elephant] Additional factors which would reinforce African elephant conservation includes coordinated international management as elephant territories are distributed broadly across the Africa plains and safari regions, and the integration of local communities into conservation planning.
[src:cites/african-elephant] Many African cultures revere the elephant as a symbol of strength and power.
[src:cites/african-elephant] It is also praised for its size, longevity, stamina, mental faculties, cooperative spirit, and loyalty.
[src:cites/african-elephant] Its religious importance is mostly totemic.
[src:cites/african-elephant] Many societies believed that their chiefs would be reincarnated as elephants.
[src:cites/african-elephant] In the 10th century, the people of Igbo-Ukwu in Nigeria buried their leaders with elephant tusks.
[src:cites/african-elephant] South Africa uses elephant tusks in their coat of arms to represent wisdom, strength, moderation and eternity.
[src:cites/african-elephant] In the western African Kingdom of Dahomey (now Benin), the elephant was associated with the 19th century rulers of the Fon people, Guezo and his son Glele.
[src:cites/african-elephant] The coat of arms of the Central African Republic features the head of an elephant in the upper left quadrant of the shield.
[src:cites/african-elephant] The version of the coat of arms of Guinea used from 1958 to 1984 featured a golden elephant in the centre of the shield.
[src:cites/african-elephant] The coat of arms of Ivory Coast features the head of an elephant as the focal point of the emblem.
[src:cites/african-elephant] The coat of arms of the Republic of the Congo has two elephants supporting the shield.
[src:cites/african-elephant] The coat of arms of Eswatini has an elephant and a lion supporting the shield.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] The **African forest elephant** (***Loxodonta cyclotis***) is an elephant species native to humid tropical forests in West Africa and the Congo Basin.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] With an average shoulder height of 2.16 m (7 ft 1 in), it is the smallest of the three living elephants.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] Both sexes have straight, down-pointing tusks, which begin to grow at the age of 1–3 years.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] The African forest elephant lives in highly sociable family groups of up to 20 individuals comprising adult cows, their daughters and sons.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] When young bulls reach sexual maturity, they separate from the family group and form loose bachelor groups for a short time, but usually stay alone.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] Adult bulls associate with family groups only during the mating season.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] The African forest elephant forages on leaves, seeds, fruit, and tree bark of at least 96 plant species.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] Since it disseminates partly digested seeds for at least 5 km (3.1 mi) through its droppings, it contributes significantly to maintaining the diversity and structure of the Guinean Forests of West Africa and the Congolese rainforests.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] During the 20th century, overhunting caused a sharp decline of the African forest elephant population, and by 2013 it was estimated that fewer than 30,000 individuals remained.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] It is threatened by habitat loss, fragmentation, and poaching.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] The conservation status of populations varies across range countries.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] Since 2021, it has been listed as Critically Endangered on the IUCN Red List.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] The African forest elephant was long considered to be a subspecies of the African elephant, together with the African bush elephant.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] Morphological and DNA analysis showed that they are two distinct species.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] The taxonomic status of the African pygmy elephant (*Loxodonta pumilio*) was uncertain for a long time.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] Phylogenetic analysis of the mitochondrial genome of nine specimens from museum collections indicates that it is an African forest elephant whose diminutive size or early maturity is due to environmental conditions.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] Phylogenetic analysis of nuclear DNA of African bush and forest elephants, Asian elephants, woolly mammoths and American mastodons revealed that the African forest elephant and African bush elephant are two distinct species that genetically diverged at least 1.9 million years ago.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] This hybridisation is suggested to have occurred around 1 million years ago, shortly prior to *Palaeoloxodon* leaving Africa.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] The African forest elephant is considerably smaller than the African bush elephant, though the size of the species has been subject to contradictory estimates.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] A 2000 study suggested that bulls of the species reach a shoulder height of 2.4–3 m (7.9–9.8 ft), and weighed 4–7 t (4.4–7.7 short tons), while cows were about 1.8–2.4 m (5.9–7.9 ft) tall at the shoulder and 2–4 t (2.2–4.4 short tons).
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] However, a 2003 study of forest elephants at a reserve in Gabon did not find any elephants taller than 2.16 m (7.1 ft).
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] The African forest elephant has grey skin, which looks yellow to reddish after wallowing.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] It is sparsely covered with black coarse hair, which is 20–200 mm (0.8–8 in) long around the tip of the tail.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] The length of the tail varies between individuals from half the height of the rump to almost touching ground.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] It has five toenails on the fore foot and four on the hind foot.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] Its oval-shaped ears have small elliptical-shaped tips, and the tip of the trunk has two finger-like processes.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] The African forest elephant's tusks are straight and point downwards, and are present in both males and females.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] The African forest elephant has pink tusks, which are thinner and harder than the tusks of the African bush elephant.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] The length and diameter vary between individuals.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] Tusks of bulls grow throughout life, tusks of cows cease growing when they are sexually mature.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] The tusks are used to push through the dense undergrowth of their habitat.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] The largest tusk recorded for the species is 2.41 m (7.9 ft) long and 60 kg (130 lb) in weight.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] A larger tusk measuring 2.96 m (9.7 ft) long and weighing 70 kg (150 lb) has been recorded, but this may belong to a forest-bush elephant hybrid.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] The average tusk size is uncertain due to measurements historically being lumped in with those of African bush elephants, but based on the sizes of the largest known tusks may be in the region of 1.6–2 m (5.2–6.6 ft) and 25–30 kg (55–66 lb).
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] Populations of the African forest elephant in Central Africa range in large contiguous rainforest tracts from Cameroon to the Democratic Republic of the Congo, with the largest stable population in Gabon, where suitable habitat covers 90% of the country.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] They are also distributed in the evergreen moist deciduous Upper Guinean forests in Ivory Coast and Ghana, in West Africa.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] A group of about 10-25 African forest elephants has been sighted on the escarpment to the east of Luanda in the Kambondo forest in 2015.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] Nonetheless, it was estimated that the population of African forest elephants in Central Africa had declined by around 86% (in the 31 years preceding 2021) due to poaching and loss of habitat.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] In places such as Cameroon, Democratic Republic of the Congo, Republic of the Congo and the Central African Republic, many areas of appropriate forest habitat have been reduced after years of warfare and human conflict.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] As of 2021, an estimated 95,000 forest elephants lived in Gabon.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] Prior to this the population had been estimated at 50,000 to 60,000 individuals.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] The African forest elephant lives in family groups.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] Groups observed in the rain forest of Gabon's Lopé National Park between 1984 and 1991 comprised between three and eight individuals.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] Groups of up to 20 individuals were observed in the Dzanga-Sangha Complex of Protected Areas, comprising adult cows, their daughters and subadult sons.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] Family members look after calves together, called allomothering.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] Once young bulls reach sexual maturity, they separate from the family group and form loose bachelor groups for a few days, but usually stay alone.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] Family groups travel about 7.8 km (4.8 mi) per day and move in a home range of up to 2,000 km2 (770 sq mi).
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] Their seasonal movement is related to the availability of ripe fruits in Primary Rainforests.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] They use a complex network of permanent trails that pass through stands of fruit trees and connect forest clearings with mineral licks.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] These trails are reused by humans and other animals.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] In Odzala-Kokoua National Park, groups were observed to frequently meet at forest clearings indicating a fission–fusion society.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] They stayed longer when other groups were also present.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] Smaller groups joined large groups, and bulls joined family units.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] The African forest elephant is an herbivore.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] Elephants observed in Lopé National Park fed mostly tree bark and leaves, and at least 72 different fruits.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] To supplement their diet with minerals, they congregate at mineral-rich waterholes and mineral licks.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] Dung piles collected in a lowland rain forest in the northern Republic of Congo contained seeds of at least 96 plant species, with a minimum of 30 intact seeds and up to 1102 large seeds of more than 1 cm (0.39 in) in a single pile.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] Based on the analysis of 855 dung piles, it has been estimated that African forest elephants disperse a daily mean of 346 large seeds per 1 km2 (0.39 sq mi) of at least 73 tree species; they transport about a third of the large seeds for more than 5 km (3.1 mi).
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] Seeds passed by elephant gut germinate faster.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] The African forest elephant is one of the most effective seed disperser in the tropics and has been referred to as the "megagardener of the forest" due to its significant role in maintaining plant diversity.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] In the Cuvette Centrale, 14 of 18 megafaunal tree species depend on seed dissemination by African forest elephants, including wild mango (*Irvingia gabonensis*), *Parinari excelsa* and *Tridesmostemon omphalocarpoides*.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] These 14 species are not able to survive without elephants.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] African forest elephants provide ecological services that maintain the composition and structure of Central African forests.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] Vocalization is a trait found among *L. cyclotis* with studies emphasizing significance in acoustic structure and their social dynamics.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] Vocalization patterns can be classified into three main types: single rumble, single broadband, and combinatorial.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] Rumbles are tonal, low-frequency calls, while broadband are calls that lack clear harmonic structures, resembling barks and roars.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] The utilization of rumbles and broadband calls in combinatorial calls may involve distinct acoustic elements, forming multi-element calls, which combine meaningless elements to generate context-specific meaningful calls.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] The African forest elephant also exhibits a more balanced distribution of combinatorial call types compared to other elephant species.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] Despite having a simpler social structure, *L. cyclotis* can display a comparable repertoire of rumble-roar call combinations than *L. africana*.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] Communication patterns vary across age and sex, with adult males typically producing more combinatorial calls than adult females.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] Additionally, certain events may provoke a behavioral change, as evidenced by lowered levels of vocalizations in response to gunfire sounds related to poaching.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] For these mammals, hearing and smell are the most important senses they possess because they do not have good eyesight.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] They can recognize and hear vibrations through the ground and can detect food sources with their sense of smell.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] Elephants are also an arrhythmic species, meaning they have the ability to see just as well in dim light as they can in the daylight.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] They are capable of doing so because the retina in their eyes adjusts nearly as quickly as light does.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] Females reach sexual maturity between the age of 8 and 12 years, depending on the population density and nutrition available.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] On average, they begin breeding at the age of 23 and give birth every 5–6 years.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] As a result, the birth rate is lower than the bush species, which starts breeding at age 12 and has a calf every 3–4 years.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] Baby elephants weigh around 105 kg (232 lb) at birth.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] Almost immediately, they can stand up and move around, allowing the mother to roam around and forage, which is also essential to reduce predation.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] The baby suckles using its mouth while its trunk is held over its head.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] Their tusks do not come until around 16 months and calves are not weaned until they are roughly 4 or 5 years old.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] By this time, their tusks are around 14 cm (5.5 in) long and begin to get in the way of suckling.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] African forest elephants have a lifespan of about 60 to 70 years and mature slowly, coming to puberty in their early teens.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] Bulls generally pass puberty within the next year or two of females.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] Between the ages of 15 and 25, bulls experience "musth", which is a hormonal state they experience marked by increased aggression.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] The male secretes fluid from the temporal gland between his ear and eye during this time.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] Younger bulls often experience musth for a shorter period of time, while older bulls do for a longer time.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] When in musth, bulls have a more erect walk with their head high and tusks inward, they may rub their heads on trees or bushes to spread the musth scent, and they may even flap their ears, accompanied by a musth rumble, so that their smell can be blown toward other elephants.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] Another behavior affiliated with musth is urination.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] Bulls allow their urine to slowly come out and spray the insides of their hind legs.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] All of these behaviors are to advertise to receptive females and competing bulls that they are in the musth state.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] Bulls only return to the herd to breed or to socialize; they do not provide parental care to their offspring but rather play a fatherly role to younger bulls to show dominance.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] Females are polyestrous, meaning they are capable of conceiving multiple times a year, which is a reason why they do not appear to have a breeding season.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] However, there does appear to be a peak in conceptions during the two rainy seasons of the year.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] Generally, the female conceives after two or three matings.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] Though the female has plenty of room in her uterus for twins, twins are rarely conceived.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] Based on the maturity, fertility, and gestation rates, African forest elephants have the capacity to increase their population by 5% annually under ideal conditions.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] African forest elephants are hunted by various hunter-gatherer groups in the Congo basin, including by Mbuti pygmies, among others.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] It is unknown how long the active hunting of elephants in the region has been practised, and it may have only begun as a response for the demand for ivory beginning in the 19th century or earlier.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] Elephants are traditionally hunted using spears, typically to stab at the lower abdomen (as is done among the Mbuti) or knees, both of which are effective at rendering the animal immobile.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] These hunters often went into the forest without food, living off of wild honey and vegetables, smearing themselves in mud, elephant dung, and charcoal made from certain plants to disguise their scent from the elephants.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] Once the traces of an elephant are detected, it was carefully tracked, before being approached from downwind and stabbed.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] It typically took several hours to several days from the first stab to the death of the elephant.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] Following the death of the animal, the Mbuti hunters returned to their homes, with the whole community moving to dismember the elephant carcass.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] Meat was shared equally among the community with the exception of a few body parts which were reserved for certain community members, with the feast on the animals remains lasting for several days.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] Elephant hunting was a dangerous activity that was known to result in the deaths of hunters.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] Both African elephant species are threatened foremost by habitat loss and habitat fragmentation following conversion of forests for plantations of non-timber crops, livestock farming, and building urban and industrial areas.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] Poaching for ivory and bushmeat is a significant threat in Central Africa.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] Because of a spike in poaching, the African forest elephant was declared Critically Endangered by the IUCN in 2021 after it was found that the population had decreased by more than 80% over 3 generations.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] Civil unrest, human encroachment, and habit fragmentation leaves some elephants confined to small patches of forest without sufficient food.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] In January 2014, International Fund for Animal Welfare undertook a relocation project at the request of the Ivory Coast government, moving four elephants from Daloa to Assagny National Park.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] So did partly worked ivory confiscated between 2013 and 2014 at warehouses in Togo comprising 4,555 kg (5.021 short tons) of tusks.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] The hard ivory of the African forest elephant makes for more enhanced carving and fetches a higher price on the black market.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] This preference is evident in Japan, where hard ivory has nearly monopolized the trade for some time.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] Premium quality bachi, a traditional Japanese plucking tool used for string instruments, is contrived exclusively from African forest elephant tusks.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] In the impenetrable and often trackless expanses of the rain forests of the Congo Basin, poaching is extremely difficult to detect and track.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] Levels of off-take, for the most part, are estimated from ivory seizures.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] The scarcely populated and unprotected forests in Central Africa are most likely becoming increasingly alluring to organized poacher gangs.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] Late in the 20th century, conservation workers established a DNA identification system to trace the origin of poached ivory.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] Due to poaching to meet high demand for ivory, the African forest elephant population approached critical levels in the 1990s and early 2000s.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] Over several decades, numbers are estimated to have fallen from approximately 700,000 to less than 100,000, with about half of the remaining population in Gabon.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] In May 2013, Sudanese poachers killed 26 elephants in the Central African Republic's Dzanga Bai World Heritage Site.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] Communications equipment, video cameras, and additional training of park guards were provided following the massacre to improve protection of the site.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] From mid-April to mid-June 2014, poachers killed 68 elephants in Garamba National Park, including young ones without tusks.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] At the request of President Ali Bongo Ondimba, twelve British soldiers traveled to Gabon in 2015 to assist in training park rangers following the poaching of many elephants in Minkebe National Park.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] On 19 August 2020, Guyvanho, a poacher who killed over 500 African forest elephants in the Nouabalé-Ndoki National Park, was convicted to 30 years in prison for charges of poaching and others.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] Guyvanho was the first poacher to be tried criminally in the Republic of the Congo, and has the longest prison sentence for a poacher in the Republic of the Congo.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] It is not ivory alone that drives African forest elephant poaching.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] Killing for bushmeat in Central Africa has evolved into an international business in recent decades with markets reaching New York and other major cities of the United States, and the industry is still on the rise.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] This illegal market poses the greatest threat not only to forest elephants where hunters can target elephants of all ages, including calves, but to all of the larger species in the forests.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] There are actions that can be taken to lower the incentive for supplying to the bushmeat market.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] Regional markets, and international trade, require the transporting of extensive amounts of animal meat which, in turn, requires the utilisation of vehicles.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] Having checkpoints on major roads and railroads can potentially help disrupt commercial networks.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] In 2006, it was estimated that 410 African forest elephants are killed yearly in the Cross-Sanaga-Bioko coastal forests.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] This database includes results from aerial surveys, dung counts, interviews with local people, and data on poaching.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] Both African elephant species have been listed by the Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species of Wild Fauna and Flora on CITES Appendix I since 1989.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] This listing banned commercial international trade of wild African elephants and their parts and derivatives by countries that signed the CITES agreement.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] Populations of Botswana, Namibia and Zimbabwe were listed in CITES Appendix II in 1997 as was the population of South Africa in 2000.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] African forest elephants are estimated to constitute up to one-third of the continent's elephant population but have been poorly studied because of the difficulty in observing them through the dense vegetation that makes up their habitat.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] Thermal imaging has facilitated observation of the species, leading to more information on their ecology, numbers, and behavior, including their interactions with elephants and other species.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] Scientists have learned more about how the elephants, who have poor night vision, negotiate their environment using only their hearing and olfactory senses.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] They also appeared to be much more active sexually during the night compared to the day, which was unexpected.
[src:cites/african-forest-elephant] Research in the tropical rainforest has shown that African forest elephants can significantly increase the forest's carbon uptake, making conservation a way to contribute to carbon storage.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] The **American black bear** (***Ursus americanus***), or simply **black bear**, is a species of medium-sized bear which is endemic to North America.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] It is the continent's smallest and most widely distributed bear species.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] It is an omnivore, with a diet varying greatly depending on season and location.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] It typically lives in largely forested areas; it will leave forests in search of food and is sometimes attracted to human communities due to the immediate availability of food.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] The International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN) lists the American black bear as a least-concern species because of its widespread distribution and a large population, estimated to be twice that of all other bear species combined.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Along with the brown bear (*Ursus arctos*), it is one of the two modern bear species not considered by the IUCN to be globally threatened with extinction.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] The American black bear is not closely related to the brown bear or polar bear, though all three species are found in North America; genetic studies reveal that they split from a common ancestor 5.05 million years ago (mya).
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] American and Asian black bears are considered sister taxa and are more closely related to each other than to the other modern species of bears.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] The ancestors of American black bears and Asian black bears diverged from sun bears 4.58 mya.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] The American black bear then split from the Asian black bear 4.08 mya.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] A small, primitive bear genus called protarctos (*U. abstrusus*) is the oldest known North American fossil member of the genus *Ursus*, dated to 4.95 mya.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] This suggests that *U. abstrusus* may be the direct ancestor of the American black bear, which evolved in North America.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] The earliest American black bear fossils, from the Early Pleistocene of Port Kennedy, Pennsylvania, greatly resemble the Asian species, though later specimens grew to sizes comparable to grizzly bears.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Once described as a precursor species (*Ursus vitabilis*), these specimens have been synonymized with *U. americanus*.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] The American black bear lived during the same period as the giant and lesser short-faced bears (*Arctodus simus* and *A. pristinus*, respectively) and the Florida spectacled bear (*Tremarctos floridanus*).
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] These tremarctine bears evolved from bears that had emigrated from Asia to the Americas 7–8 mya.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] The giant and lesser short-faced bears are thought to have been heavily carnivorous and the Florida spectacled bear more herbivorous, while the American black bears remained arboreal omnivores, like their Asian ancestors.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] From the Holocene to the present, American black bears seem to have shrunk in size, but this has been disputed because of problems with dating these fossil specimens.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] The American black bear's generalist behavior allowed it to exploit a wider variety of foods and has been given as a reason why, of these three genera, it alone survived climate and vegetative changes through the last Ice Age while the other, more specialized North American predators became extinct.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] However, both *Arctodus* and *Tremarctos* had survived several other, previous ice ages.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] After these prehistoric ursids became extinct at the end of the Pleistocene, American black bears, brown bears and polar bears were the only remaining bears in North America.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] American black bears are reproductively compatible with several other bear species and occasionally produce hybrid offspring.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] According to Jack Hanna's *Monkeys on the Interstate*, a bear captured in Sanford, Florida, was thought to have been the offspring of an escaped female Asian black bear and a male American black bear.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] In 1859, an American black bear and a Eurasian brown bear were bred together in the London Zoo, but the three cubs that were born died before they reached maturity.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] A bear shot in autumn 1986 in Michigan was thought by some to be an American black bear/grizzly bear hybrid, because of its unusually large size and its proportionately larger brain case and skull.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] DNA testing was unable to determine whether it was a large American black bear or a grizzly bear.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Sixteen subspecies are traditionally recognized; however, a 2015 genetic study did not support designating some of these, such as the Florida black bear, as distinct subspecies.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Historically, American black bears occupied the majority of North America's forested regions.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Today, they are primarily limited to sparsely settled, forested areas.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] American black bears currently inhabit much of their original Canadian range, though they seldom occur in the southern farmlands of Alberta, Saskatchewan and Manitoba; they have been extirpated on Prince Edward Island since 1937.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Surveys taken in the mid-1990s found the Canadian black bear population to be between 396,000 and 476,000 in seven provinces; this estimate excludes populations in New Brunswick, the Northwest Territories, Nova Scotia and Saskatchewan.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] All provinces indicated stable populations of American black bears over the 2000s.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] The current range in the United States is constant throughout most of the Northeast and within the Appalachian Mountains almost continuously from Maine to northern Georgia, the northern Midwest, the Rocky Mountain region, the West Coast and Alaska.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] However, it becomes increasingly fragmented or absent in other regions.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Despite this, American black bears in those areas seem to have expanded their range in recent decades, such as with sightings in Ohio, Illinois, southern Indiana, and western Nebraska.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Sightings of itinerant black bears in the Driftless Area of southeastern Minnesota, northeastern Iowa, and southwestern Wisconsin are common.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] In 2019, biologists with the Iowa Department of Natural Resources confirmed documentation of an American black bear living year-round in woodlands near the town of Decorah in northeastern Iowa, believed to be the first instance of a resident black bear in Iowa since the 1880s.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Surveys taken from 35 states in the early 1990s indicated that American black bear populations were either stable or increasing, except in Idaho and New Mexico.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] The population in the United States was estimated to range between 339,000 and 465,000 in 2011, though this estimate does not include data from Alaska, Idaho, South Dakota, Texas or Wyoming, whose populations were not recorded in the survey.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] In California there were an estimated 25,000-35,000 black bears in 2017, making it the largest population of the species in any of the 48 contiguous United States.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] In 2020 there were about 1,500 bears in Great Smoky Mountains National Park, where the population density is about two per square mile.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] In western North Carolina, the black bear population has dramatically increased from about 3,000 in the early 2000s to over 8,000 in the 2020s.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] As of 1993, known black bear populations in Mexico existed in four areas, though knowledge on the distribution of populations outside those areas has not been updated since 1959.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Mexico is the only country where the species is classified as "endangered".
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Throughout their range, habitats preferred by American black bears have a few shared characteristics.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] They are often found in areas with relatively inaccessible terrain, thick understory vegetation and large quantities of edible material (especially masts).
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Although found in the largest numbers in wild, undisturbed areas and rural regions, American black bears can adapt to surviving in some numbers in peri-urban regions, as long as they contain easily accessible foods and some vegetative coverage.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] In most of the contiguous United States, American black bears today are usually found in heavily vegetated mountainous areas, from 400 to 3,000 m (1,300 to 9,800 ft) in elevation.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] For American black bears living in the American Southwest and Mexico, habitat usually consists of stands of chaparral and Pinyon–juniper woodlands.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] In this region, bears occasionally move to more open areas to feed on prickly pear cactus.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] At least two distinct, prime habitat types are inhabited in the Southeastern United States.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] American black bears in the southern Appalachian Mountains survive in predominantly oak-hickory and mixed mesophytic forests.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] In the coastal areas of the southeast (such as Florida, the Carolinas and Louisiana), bears inhabit a mixture of flatwoods, bays and swampy hardwood sites.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] In the northeastern part of the range (the United States and Canada), prime habitat consists of a forest canopy of hardwoods such as beech, maple, birch and coniferous species.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Corn crops and oak-hickory mast are also common sources of food in some sections of the northeast; small, thick swampy areas provide excellent refuge cover largely in stands of white cedar.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Along the Pacific coast, redwood, Sitka spruce and hemlocks predominate as overstory cover.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Within these northern forest types are early successional areas important for American black bears, such as fields of brush, wet and dry meadows, high tidelands, riparian areas and a variety of mast-producing hardwood species.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] The spruce-fir forest dominates much of the range of the American black bear in the Rockies.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Important non-forested areas here are wet meadows, riparian areas, avalanche chutes, roadsides, burns, sidehill parks and subalpine ridgetops.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] In areas where human development is relatively low, such as stretches of Canada and Alaska, American black bears tend to be found more regularly in lowland regions.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] In parts of eastern Canada, especially Labrador, American black bears have adapted exclusively to semi-open areas that are more typical habitat in North America for brown bears (likely due to the absence there of brown and polar bears, as well as other large carnivore species).
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] showing top, bottom and lateral aspects.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] The skulls of American black bears are broad, with narrow muzzles and large jaw hinges.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] In Virginia, the length of adult bear skulls was found to average 26.2 to 31.7 cm (10.3 to 12.5 in).
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Across its range, the longest reported skull measured from 23.5 to 35 cm (9.3 to 13.8 in).
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Sexual dimorphism can be seen in the tendency for females to have slenderer and more pointed faces, and conversely, for larger cheek teeth in males.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Their claws are short and curved, being thickest at the base then tapering to a point, and most often black or grayish-brown in color.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Claws from both hind and front legs are almost identical in length, though the curvature of foreclaws tends to be greater.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] The soles of the feet are black or brownish and are naked, leathery and deeply wrinkled.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] The hind legs are relatively longer than those of Asian black bears.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] The ears are small and rounded, as well as being set well back on the head.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] American black bears are highly dexterous, being capable of opening screw cap containers and manipulating door latches.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] They also have great physical strength; a bear weighing 120 lb (54 kg) was observed flipping over flat rocks weighing 310 to 325 lb (141 to 147 kg) with a single foreleg.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] They move with a rhythmic, sure-footed gait and can run at speeds of up to 25–30 mph (40–48 km/h).
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] American black bears have good eyesight and have been proven experimentally to be able to learn visual color discrimination tasks faster than chimpanzees and just as fast as domestic dogs.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] They are also capable of rapidly learning to distinguish different shapes, such as small triangles, circles and squares.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Adults typically range from 120 to 188 cm (47 to 74 in) in head-and-body length, and 63 to 103.5 cm (24.8 to 40.7 in) in shoulder height.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Although the American black bear is the smallest bear species in North America (smaller than the brown and polar bears), large males exceed the size of other bear species in other continents.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Weight tends to vary according to age, sex, health and season.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Adult males typically weigh between 60–300 kg (130–660 lb) with females averaging between 33% and 50% less at 40–150 kg (88–331 lb).
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Seasonal variation in weight is very pronounced: in autumn, their pre-den weight tends to be 30% higher than in spring, when black bears emerge from their dens.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] In California, studies indicate that the average adult mass is 86 kg (190 lb) in males and 58 kg (128 lb) in females.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Adults in Yukon Flats National Wildlife Refuge in east-central Alaska were found to average 87.3 kg (192 lb) in males and 63.4 kg (140 lb) in females, whereas on Kuiu Island in southeastern Alaska (where nutrient dense salmon are readily available) adults averaged 115 kg (254 lb).
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] In Great Smoky Mountains National Park, adult males averaged 112 kg (247 lb) and adult females averaged 47 kg (104 lb) per one study.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] In one of the largest studies on regional body mass, bears in British Columbia averaged 73.7 kg (162 lb) in 89 females and 103.1 kg (227 lb) in 243 males.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] In Yellowstone National Park, a study found that adult males averaged 119 kg (262 lb) and adult females averaged 67 kg (148 lb).
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Black bears in north-central Minnesota averaged 70 kg (150 lb) in 163 females and 125 kg (276 lb) in 77 males.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] In New York, the males average 136 kg (300 lb) and females 72.6 kg (160 lb).
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] In Waterton Lakes National Park, Alberta, adults averaged 125 to 128 kg (276 to 282 lb).
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] The biggest wild American black bear ever recorded was a male from New Brunswick, shot in November 1972, that weighed 409 kg (902 lb) after it had been dressed, meaning it weighed an estimated 500 kg (1,100 lb) in life and measured 2.41 m (7 ft 11 in) long.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Another notably outsized wild American black bear, weighing in at 408 kg (899 lb), was the cattle-killer shot in December 1921 on the Moqui Reservation in Arizona.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] The record-sized American black bear from New Jersey was shot in Morris County December 2011 and scaled 376.5 kg (830 lb).
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] The Pennsylvania state record weighed 399 kg (880 lb) and was shot in November 2010 in Pike County.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] The North American Bear Center, located in Ely, Minnesota, is home to the world's largest captive male and female American black bears.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Honey, the female, weighed 219.6 kg (484 lb) in the fall of 2007.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] The fur is soft, with dense underfur and long, coarse, thick guard hairs.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] The fur is not as shaggy or coarse as that of brown bears.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] American black bear skins can be distinguished from those of Asian black bears by the lack of a white blaze on the chest and hairier footpads.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Despite their name, black bears show a great deal of color variation.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Individual coat colors can range from white, blonde, cinnamon, light brown or dark chocolate brown to jet black, with many intermediate variations existing.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Silvery-gray American black bears with a blue luster (found mostly on the flanks) occur along a portion of coastal Alaska and British Columbia.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] White to cream-colored American black bears occur in the coastal islands and the adjacent mainland of southwestern British Columbia.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Albino individuals have also been recorded.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Black coats tend to predominate in humid areas, such as Maine, New England, New York, Tennessee, Michigan and western Washington.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Approximately 70% of all American black bears are black, though only 50% in the Rocky Mountains are black.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Many in northwestern North America are cinnamon, blonde or light brown in color and thus may sometimes be mistaken for grizzly bears.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Grizzly (and other types of brown) bears can be distinguished by their shoulder hump, larger size and broader, more concave skull.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Their keenest sense is smell, which is about seven times more sensitive than a domestic dog's.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] They are excellent and strong swimmers, swimming for pleasure and to feed (largely on fish).
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] They regularly climb trees to feed, escape enemies and hibernate.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Four of the eight modern bear species are habitually arboreal (the most arboreal species, the American and Asian black bears and the sun bear, being fairly closely related).
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Their arboreal abilities tend to decline with age.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] They may be active at any time of the day or night, although they mainly forage by night.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Bears living near human habitations tend to be more extensively nocturnal, while those living near brown bears tend to be more often diurnal.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] American black bears tend to be territorial and non-gregarious in nature.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] However, at abundant food sources (e.g. spawning salmon or garbage dumps), they may congregate and dominance hierarchies form, with the largest, most powerful males dominating the most fruitful feeding spots.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] They mark their territories by rubbing their bodies against trees and clawing at the bark.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Annual ranges held by mature male bears tend to be very large, though there is some variation.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] On Long Island off the coast of Washington, ranges average 5 sq mi (13 km2), whereas on the Ungava Peninsula in Canada ranges can average up to 1,000 sq mi (2,600 km2), with some male bears traveling as far as 4,349 sq mi (11,260 km2) at times of food shortages.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Bears may communicate with various vocal and non-vocal sounds.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Tongue-clicking and grunting are the most common sounds and are made in cordial situations to conspecifics, offspring and occasionally humans.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] When at ease, they produce a loud rumbling hum.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] During times of fear or nervousness, bears may moan, huff or blow air.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Warning sounds include jaw-clicking and lip-popping.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] In aggressive interactions, black bears produce guttural pulsing calls that may sound like growling.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Cubs squeal, bawl or scream when anxious and make a motor-like humming sound when comfortable or nursing.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] American black bears often mark trees using their teeth and claws as a form of communication with other bears, a behavior common to many species of bears.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Sows usually produce their first litter at the age of 3 to 5 years, with those living in more developed areas tending to get pregnant at younger ages.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] The breeding period usually occurs in the June–July period, though it can extend to August in the species' northern range.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] The breeding period lasts for two to three months.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Males try to mate with several females, but large, dominant ones may violently claim a female if another mature male comes near.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Sows tend to be short-tempered with their mates after copulating.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] The fertilized eggs undergo delayed development and do not implant in the female's womb until November.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] The gestation period lasts 235 days, and litters are usually born in late January to early February.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Litter size is between one and six cubs, typically two or three.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] They are born with fine, gray, down-like hair and their hind quarters are underdeveloped.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] They typically open their eyes after 28–40 days and begin walking after 5 weeks.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Cubs are dependent on their mother's milk for 30 weeks and will reach independence at 16–18 months.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] At 6 weeks, they attain 900 g (2.0 lb), by 8 weeks they reach 2.5 kg (5.5 lb) and by 6 months they weigh 18 to 27 kg (40 to 60 lb).
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] They reach sexual maturity at 3 years and attain their full growth at 5 years.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] The average lifespan in the wild is 18 years, and it is quite possible for wild individuals to survive for more than 23 years.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] The record age of a wild individual was 39 years, while that in captivity was 44 years.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] The average annual survival rate is variable, ranging from 86% in Florida to 73% in Virginia and North Carolina.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] In Minnesota, 99% of wintering adult bears were able to survive the hibernation cycle in one study.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] A study of American black bears in Nevada found that the amount of annual mortality of a population of bears in wilderness areas was 0%, whereas in developed areas in the state this figure rose to 83%.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Survival in subadults is generally less assured.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] In Alaska 14–17% of subadult males and 30–48% of subadult females were found in a study to survive to adulthood.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Across the range, the estimated number of cubs who survive past their first year is 60%.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] With the exception of the rare confrontation with an adult brown bear or a gray wolf pack, adult black bears are not usually subject to natural predation.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Scats with fur inside of them and a carcass of an adult sow with puncture marks in the skull indicate black bears may occasionally be killed by jaguars in the southern parts of their range.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] In such scenarios, the big cat would have the advantage if it ambushed the bear, killing it with a crushing bite to the back of the skull.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Cubs tend to be more vulnerable to predation than adults, with known predators including bobcats, coyotes, cougars, gray wolves, brown bears and other bears of their own species.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Many of these will stealthily snatch small cubs right from under the sleeping mother.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] There is record of a golden eagle snatching a yearling cub.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Once out of hibernation, mother bears may be able to fight off most potential predators.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Even cougars will be displaced by an angry mother bear if they are discovered stalking the cubs.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Flooding of dens after birth may also occasionally kill newborn cubs.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Bear fatalities are mainly attributable to human activities.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Seasonally, thousands of black bears are hunted legally across North America, and some are illegally poached or trapped unregulated.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Auto collisions also may kill many black bears annually.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] American black bears are now considered highly efficient hibernators.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] The physiology of American black bears in the wild is closely related to that of bears in captivity.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Understanding the physiology of bears in the wild is vital to the bear's success in captivity.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] The bears enter their dens in October and November, although in the southernmost areas of their range (i.e.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Florida, Mexico, the southeastern United States), only pregnant females and mothers with yearling cubs will enter hibernation.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Prior to that time, they can put on up to 14 kg (30 lb) of body fat to get them through the several months during which they fast.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Hibernation typically lasts 3–8 months, depending on regional climate.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Hibernating bears spend their time in hollowed-out dens in tree cavities, under logs or rocks, in banks, caves, or culverts, and in shallow depressions.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Although naturally-made dens are occasionally used, most dens are dug out by the bear.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] During their time in hibernation, an American black bear's heart rate drops from 40 to 50 beats per minute to 8 beats per minute, and the metabolic rate can drop to a quarter of the bear's (non-hibernating) basal metabolic rate.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] These reductions in metabolic rate and heart rate do not appear to decrease the bear's ability to heal injuries during hibernation.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Their circadian rhythm stays intact during hibernation.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] This allows the bear to sense the changes in the day based on the ambient temperature caused by the sun's position in the sky.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] It has also been shown that ambient light exposure and low disturbance levels (that is to say, wild bears in ambient light conditions) directly correlate with their activity levels.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] The bear keeping track of the changing days allows it to awaken from hibernation at the appropriate time of year to conserve as much energy as possible.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] The hibernating bear does not display the same rate of muscle and bone atrophy relative to other nonhibernatory animals that are subject to long periods of inactivity due to ailment or old age.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] A hibernating bear only loses approximately half the muscular strength compared to that of a well-nourished, inactive human.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] The bear's bone mass does not change in geometry or mineral composition during hibernation, which implies that the bear's conservation of bone mass during hibernation is caused by a biological mechanism.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] During hibernation American black bears retain all excretory waste, leading to the development of a hardened mass of fecal material in the colon known as a fecal plug.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Leptin is released into the bear's systems to suppress appetite.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] The retention of waste during hibernation (specifically in minerals such as calcium) may play a role in the bear's resistance to atrophy.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] The body temperature does not drop significantly, like other mammalian hibernators (staying around 35 °C (95 °F)) and they remain somewhat alert and active.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] If the winter is mild enough, they may wake up and forage for food.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Females also give birth in February and nurture their cubs until the snow melts.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] During winter, American black bears consume 25–40% of their body weight.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Researchers have found that bears have adaptive reversible insulin resistance.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] During their fattening phase bears become hypersensitive to insulin but in the winter they switch and become more insulin resistant, as well as activating anti-inflammatory genes to resist kidney damage.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Many of the physiological changes an American black bear exhibits during hibernation are retained slightly post-hibernation.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Upon exiting hibernation, bears retain a reduced heart rate and basal metabolic rate.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] The metabolic rate of a hibernating bear will remain at a reduced level for up to 21 days after hibernation.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] After emerging from their winter dens in spring, they wander their home ranges for two weeks so that their metabolism accustoms itself to the activity.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] In mountainous areas, they seek southerly slopes at lower elevations for forage and move to northerly and easterly slopes at higher elevations as summer progresses.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] The time that American black bears emerge from hibernation varies.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Factors affecting this include temperature, flooding, and hunger.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] In southern areas, they may wake up in midwinter.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Further north, they may not be seen until late March, April, or even early May.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Bears at lower altitudes tend to emerge earlier.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Mature males tend to come out earliest, followed by immature males and females, and lastly mothers with cubs.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Mothers with yearling cubs are seen before those with newborns.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Generally, American black bears are largely crepuscular in foraging activity, though they may actively feed at any time.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Up to 85% of their diet consists of vegetation, though they tend to dig less than brown bears, eating far fewer roots, bulbs, corms and tubers than the latter species.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] When initially emerging from hibernation, they will seek to feed on carrion from winter-killed animals and newborn ungulates.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] As the spring temperature warms, American black bears seek new shoots of many plant species, especially new grasses, wetland plants and forbs.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Young shoots and buds from trees and shrubs during the spring period are important to bears emerging from hibernation, as they assist in rebuilding muscle and strengthening the skeleton and are often the only digestible foods available at that time.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] During summer, the diet largely comprises fruits, especially berries and soft mast such as buds and drupes.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] During the autumn hyperphagia, feeding becomes virtually the full-time task.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Hard mast becomes the most important part of the diet in autumn and may even partially dictate the species' distribution.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Favored mast such as hazelnuts, oak acorns and whitebark pine nuts may be consumed by the hundreds each day by a single bear during the fall.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] During the fall period, bears may also habitually raid the nut caches of tree squirrels.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Also extremely important in fall are berries such as huckleberries and buffalo berries.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Bears living in areas near human settlements or around a considerable influx of recreational human activity often come to rely on foods inadvertently provided by humans, especially during summertime.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] These include refuse, birdseed, agricultural products and honey from apiaries.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] The majority of the animal portion of their diet consists of insects, such as bees, yellow jackets, ants, beetles and their larvae.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] American black bears are also fond of honey and will gnaw through trees if hives are too deeply set into the trunks for them to reach it with their paws.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Once the hive is breached, the bears will scrape the honeycombs together with their paws and eat them, regardless of stings from the bees.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Bears that live in northern coastal regions (especially the Pacific Coast) will fish for salmon during the night, as their black fur is easily spotted by salmon in the daytime.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Other bears, such as the white-furred Kermode bears of the islands of western Canada, have a 30% greater success rate in catching salmon than their black-furred counterparts.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Other fish, including suckers, trout and catfish, are readily caught whenever possible.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Although American black bears do not often engage in active predation of other large animals for much of the year, the species will regularly prey on mule and white-tailed deer fawns in spring, given the opportunity.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Bears may catch the scent of hiding fawns when foraging for something else and then sniff them out and pounce on them.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] As the fawns reach 10 days of age, they can outmaneuver the bears, and their scent is soon ignored until the next year.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] American black bears have also been recorded similarly preying on elk calves in Idaho and moose calves in Alaska.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Predation on adult deer is rare, but it has been recorded.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] They may even hunt prey up to the size of adult female moose, which are considerably larger than themselves, by ambushing them.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] There is at least one record of a male American black bear killing two bull elk over the course of six days by chasing them into deep snow banks, which impeded their movements.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] In Labrador, American black bears are exceptionally carnivorous, living largely off caribou, usually young, injured, old, sickly or dead specimens, and rodents such as voles.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] This is believed to be due to a paucity of edible plant life in this sub-Arctic region and a local lack of competing large carnivores (including other bear species).
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Like brown bears, American black bears try to use surprise to ambush their prey and target the weak, injured, sickly or dying animals in the herds.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Once a deer fawn is captured, it is frequently torn apart alive while feeding.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] If it is able to capture a mother deer in spring, the bear frequently begins feeding on the udder of lactating females, but generally prefers meat from the viscera.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Bears often drag their prey to cover, preferring to feed in seclusion.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] The skin of large prey is stripped back and turned inside out, with the skeleton usually left largely intact.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Unlike gray wolves and coyotes, bears rarely scatter the remains of their kills.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Vegetation around the carcass is usually matted down, and their droppings are frequently found nearby.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Bears may attempt to cover remains of larger carcasses, though they do not do so with the same frequency as cougars and grizzly bears.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] They will readily consume eggs and nestlings of various birds and can easily access many tree nests, even the huge nests of bald eagles.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Bears have been reported stealing deer and other game from human hunters.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Over much of their range, American black bears are assured scavengers that can intimidate, using their large size and considerable strength, and if necessary dominate other predators in confrontations over carcasses.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] However, on occasions where they encounter Kodiak or grizzly bears, the larger two brown subspecies dominate them.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] American black bears tend to escape competition from brown bears by being more active in the daytime and living in more densely forested areas.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Violent interactions, resulting in the deaths of American black bears, have been recorded in Yellowstone National Park.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] American black bears do occasionally compete with cougars over carcasses.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Like brown bears, they will sometimes steal kills from cougars.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] One study found that both bear species visited 24% of cougar kills in Yellowstone and Glacier National Parks, usurping 10% of the carcasses.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Another study found that American black bears visited 48% of cougar kills in summer in Colorado and 77% of kills in California.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] As a result, the cats spend more time killing and less time feeding on each kill.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] American black bear interactions with gray wolves are much rarer than with brown bears, due to differences in habitat preferences.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] The majority of American black bear encounters with wolves occur in the species' northern range, with no interactions being recorded in Mexico.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Despite the American black bear being more powerful on a one-to-one basis, packs of wolves have been recorded to kill black bears on numerous occasions without eating them.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Unlike brown bears, American black bears frequently lose against wolves in disputes over kills.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Wolf packs typically kill American black bears when the larger animals are in their hibernation cycle.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] There is at least one record of an American black bear killing a wolverine (*Gulo gulo*) in a dispute over food in Yellowstone National Park.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] Anecdotal cases of alligator predation on American black bears have been reported, though such cases may involve assaults on cubs.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p01] At least one jaguar (*Panthera onca*) has been recorded to have attacked and eaten a black bear: "El Jefe", the jaguar famous for being the first jaguar seen in the United States in over a century.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p02] Black bears feature prominently in the stories of some of North America's indigenous peoples.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p02] One tale tells of how the black bear was a creation of the Great Spirit, while the grizzly bear was created by the Evil Spirit.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p02] In the mythology of the Haida, Tlingit and Tsimshian people of the northwest coast, mankind first learned to respect bears when a girl married the son of a black bear chieftain.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p02] In Kwakwa̱ka̱ʼwakw mythology, black and brown bears became enemies when Grizzly Bear Woman killed Black Bear Woman for being lazy.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p02] Black Bear Woman's children, in turn, killed Grizzly Bear Woman's children.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p02] The Navajo believed that the Big Black Bear was chief among the bears of the four directions surrounding Sun's house and would pray to it in order to be granted its protection during raids.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p02] Sleeping Bear Dunes in Michigan is named after a Native American legend, where a female bear and her two cubs swam across Lake Michigan to escape a fire on the Wisconsin shore.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p02] The mother bear reached the shore and waited for her cubs, but they did not make it across.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p02] Two islands mark where the cubs drowned, while the dune marks the spot where the mother bear waited.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p02] Richard Steiff, the creator of the teddy bear, made the toy in 1902 under Margarete Steiff's felt goods company.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p02] The toys were brought to the US and gained mass popularity after a newspaper told the story of Theodore Roosevelt refusing to shoot a black bear cub tied to a tree.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p02] The fictional character Winnie-the-Pooh was named after Winnipeg, a female cub that lived at the London Zoo from 1915 until her death in 1934.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p02] A cub, who in the spring of 1950 was caught in the Capitan Gap Fire, was made into the living representative of Smokey Bear, the mascot of the United States Forest Service.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p02] Terrible Ted was a de-toothed and de-clawed bear who was forced to perform as a pro wrestler and whose "career" lasted from the 1950s to the 1970s.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p02] Clark's Bears, previously named Clark's Trading Post, is a visitor attraction in Lincoln, New Hampshire known for its trained bear shows since 1949.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p02] The American black bear is the mascot of the University of Maine and Baylor University, the latter of which houses two live bears on campus.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p02] Although an adult bear is quite capable of killing a human, American black bears typically avoid confronting humans.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p02] Unlike grizzly bears, which became a subject of fearsome legend among the European settlers of North America, black bears were rarely considered overly dangerous, even though they lived in areas where the pioneers had settled.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p02] American black bears rarely attack when confronted by humans and usually only make mock charges, emit blowing noises and swat the ground with their forepaws.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p02] The number of attacks on humans is higher than those by brown bears in North America, but this is largely because black bears considerably outnumber brown bears.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p02] Compared to brown bear attacks, aggressive encounters with black bears rarely lead to serious injury.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p02] Most attacks tend to be motivated by hunger rather than territoriality and thus victims have a higher probability of surviving by fighting back rather than submitting.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p02] Unlike female brown bears, female American black bears are not as protective of their cubs and rarely attack humans in the vicinity of the cubs.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p02] However, occasionally such attacks do occur.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p02] The worst recorded attack occurred in May 1978, in which a bear killed three teenagers fishing in Algonquin Provincial Park in Ontario.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p02] Another exceptional attack occurred in August 1997 in Liard River Hot Springs Provincial Park in British Columbia, when an emaciated bear attacked a mother and child, killing the mother and a man who intervened.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p02] The bear was shot while mauling a fourth victim.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p02] The majority of attacks happened in national parks, usually near campgrounds, where the bears had habituated too close to human proximity and food.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p02] Of 1,028 incidents of aggressive acts toward humans, recorded from 1964 to 1976 in the Great Smoky Mountains National Park, 107 resulted in injury and occurred mainly in tourist hot spots where people regularly fed the bears handouts.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p02] In almost every case where open garbage dumps that attracted bears were closed and handouts ceased, the number of aggressive encounters dropped.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p02] However, in the Liard River Hot Springs case, the bear was apparently dependent on a local garbage dump that had closed and so was starving to death.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p02] Attempts to relocate bears are typically unsuccessful, as the bears seem able to return to their home range, even without familiar landscape cues.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p02] A limitation of food sources in early spring and wild berry and nut crop failures in summer may contribute to bears regularly feeding from human-based food sources.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p02] These bears often eat crops, especially during autumn hyperphagia when natural foods are scarce.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p02] Favored crops include apples, oats and corn.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p02] American black bears can do extensive damage in areas of the northwestern United States by stripping the bark from trees and feeding on the cambium.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p02] Livestock depredations occur mostly in spring.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p02] Although they occasionally hunt adult cattle and horses, they seem to prefer smaller prey such as sheep, goats, pigs and young calves.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p02] They usually kill by biting the neck and shoulders, though they may break the neck or back of the prey with blows with the paws.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p02] Evidence of a bear attack includes claw marks and is often found on the neck, back and shoulders of larger animals.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p02] Surplus killing of sheep and goats is common.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p02] American black bears have been known to frighten livestock herds over cliffs, causing injuries and death to many animals; whether this is intentional is not known.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p02] Occasionally bears kill pets, especially domestic dogs, which are most prone to harass a bear.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p02] It is not recommended to use unleashed dogs to deter bear attacks.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p02] Although large, aggressive dogs can sometimes cause a bear to run, if pressed, angry bears often turn the tables and end up chasing the dogs in return.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p02] A bear in pursuit of a pet dog can threaten both canid and human lives.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p02] The hunting of American black bears has taken place since the initial peopling of the Americas.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p02] The first piece of evidence dates to a Clovis site at Lehner Ranch, Arizona.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p02] Partially calcined teeth of a 3-month old black bear cub came from a roasting pit, suggesting the bear cub was eaten.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p02] The surrounding charcoal was dated to the Early Holocene (10,940 BP).
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p02] Black bear remains also appear to be associated with early peoples in Tlapacoya, Mexico.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p02] Native Americans increasingly utilized black bears during the Holocene, particularly in the late Holocene upper Midwest, e.g., Hopewell and Mississippian cultures.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p02] Some Native American tribes, in admiration for the American black bear's intelligence, would decorate the heads of bears they killed with trinkets and place them on blankets.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p02] Tobacco smoke would be wafted into the disembodied head's nostrils by the hunter that dealt the killing blow, who would compliment the animal for its courage.
[src:cites/american-black-bear-p02] The Kutchin typically hunted American black bears during their hibernation cycle.
